<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge orders religious community to comply in custody case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) - Court proceedings Friday revealed that
members of the Bruderhof religious community sought in a custody
battle by three former members may be in England and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bruderhofs focus on Christ's spirit and teachings in the Sermon
on the Mount. They believe in community living, don't own private
property and share everything. Money is held commonly, decisions
are made jointly and individual members work in the community's
shops, making playthings and equipment for handicapped children.
</P>
<P>
   The women and children are believed to be part of the Bruderhof
community in Ulster County.
</P>
<P>
   The fathers - Joseph Idiong, Ebong Ebong and Basil Ebong -
charge that they have been prevented from seeing their children
since being evicted from the religious group three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ebong returned to the Bruderhof community in
Farmington, Pa., where he was living, following a trip to Nigeria,
only to find that he could not get back into the community because
he had questioned the Bruderhof leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Ebong said he saw his children once after that.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is frightening,'' said Mike Mauceri, a lawyer representing
Ebong. ''They (Bruderhof) have created a totalitarian community
with consenting adults and children.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Bruderhof Community in Woodcrest said that
in view of the ''concern and safety of the children involved, we
don't believe it is appropriate to comment at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   During a rigorous two-hour testimony, Joe Keiderling, vice
president of the Bruderhof Communities in New York Inc., said two
of the women were believed to be in Bruderhof communities in
Robertsbridge and Dover counties, England. The third one is said to
be in a Bruderhof community in Farmington, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mary Work, who is hearing the petitions, ordered a report
of the current case to be sent by overnight mail to the two women
in England. She did not order an appearance for the Pennsylvania
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are making it simply impossible to find the children,''
said Steve Franzman, a court-appointed legal guardian. The lawyers
for the three men charged that the women and children had been
whisked away to multiple locations right after members of the
Bruderhof got wind of the case.
</P>
<P>
   There are Bruderhof communities in Catskill in Greene County,
Walden in Orange County, Rifton and Ulster Park in Ulster County,
Farmington, Pa., England and Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
