<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Go to Martha's Vineyard  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- Now that the Republican convention is
over, ''it's our turn,'' President Clinton said Friday, as he
tossed a few scraps of red political meat to a hungry crowd of
partisan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept the tone light and the humor dry in his first
political remarks since George W. Bush was formally nominated as
the GOP presidential standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just finished the Republican convention and now it's our
turn,'' Clinton remarked to eager applause at a posh fund-raising
party to benefit his wife's campaign for Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats gather next weekend in Los Angeles for their
convention, which will nominate Vice President Al Gore. Clinton
addresses the convention on Aug. 14, along with his wife, Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Clinton and his family have returned to
Martha's Vineyard, their regular summer haunt, for a vacation that
is as much about fund raising as fun.
</P>
<P>
   The president helped bring in an estimated $172,000 for Mrs.
Clinton's campaign Friday, at the nearby Nantucket home of
perennial Democratic hosts Smith and Elizabeth Bagley.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's one thing that we apparently agree on -- that the
country is in good shape,'' Clinton said of the rival political
parties. ''And I appreciate that act of uncommon generosity on
their part,'' Clinton added. ''We disagree on how it happened and
what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughed, egging him on, but Clinton declined to
reprise the sarcastic put-downs of Bush that were a sidelight to
the convention this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have to say anything bad about our opponents as
people, and if I have anything to say about it, the Democrats won't
do that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president expects to raise about $1.3 million at four
fund-raising speeches between Friday and Sunday. All but one of the
events benefit his wife's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very hard for me to say anything that is not ...
sappy,'' Clinton said before delivering a testimonial to Mrs.
Clinton's record of public service. ''I'm always afraid I'll be
over the top or ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, it's off to Hyannis Port and the Kennedy
family compound. Clinton expects to help Maryland Lt. Gov. Kathleen
Kennedy Townsend raise $800,000 for her expected gubernatorial
race.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton headlines two events on Martha's Vineyard
that benefit his wife's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he will probably play a few rounds of golf. Good
weather was predicted for the weekend, after two weeks of
intermittent rain.
</P>
<P>
   The first family has visited this quaint island off the coast of
Massachusetts each summer of Clinton's presidency except 1996, when
they vacationed in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the family's shortest stay yet -- just a long
weekend. Clinton, his wife and daughter Chelsea, accompanied by dog
Buddy, lost about two hours of even that brief vacation when they
left the White House later than expected on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton brought his briefcase, and an aide was seen stuffing a
paper bag marked ''beach towels'' into the presidential helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people were lined up at the sand-strewn airport at
Martha's Vineyard to greet the Clintons, including regular
presidential golfing buddy Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the family stayed on the island about a week before
decamping for fund raising and another short vacation in upstate
New York. While there, they bought a $1.7 million house in
Chappaqua, north of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
