<HEADLINE> Clinton To Make Day Trip To Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is drawing the wrath of
Colombia's largest guerrilla movement by planning a visit to that
country Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet with President Andres Pastrana in the port
city of Cartagena to discuss ways of curbing U.S.-bound drug flows.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Congress approved $1.3 billion in assistance to
Colombia, mostly in training and equipment for military units
assigned to counter-narcotics activities.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is the world's largest coca producer. The government
also must contend with two determined guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Antonio Lozada, a spokesman for the FARC guerrilla
movement, said Friday that Clinton's stopover was ''clear
evidence'' that the United States was using the guise of the war on
drugs to violate Colombia's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe this is a visit by a president who is a
friend of the Colombian public, but exactly the opposite,'' said
Lozada, whose rebel army is believed to be about 20,000 strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a visit by a head of state that ... comes ready to
grossly intervene in the internal affairs of our country.'' He
spoke in a telephone interview from southern Colombia's
guerrilla-controlled demilitarized zone.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in a statement that it is ''profoundly in the
interest of the United States'' for Colombia to succeed in its
efforts to seek peace, fight illicit drugs, build its economy and
protect democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He will be joined on the trip by House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., and Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del. Undersecretary of State
Thomas Pickering will travel to Colombia next week to help lay the
groundwork for the trip and also to speak to a conference of
business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Clinton's first trip to Colombia, and he will go down
and back on the same day. A U.S. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said an overnight stay was ruled out for security
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The visit mirrors a visit former President Bush made in February
1990 when, highlighting his administration's anti-drug campaign,
took a day trip to Cartagena. Bush was joined there by Colombia's
president and leaders from other Andean countries.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
