<HEADLINE> Turkey Cops Detain 25 Protesters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Police detained Saturday 25 people for
holding a protest denouncing Turkey's new prison system, which
critics believe will leave hundreds of inmates isolated and
vulnerable to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, thousands of inmates will be moved away
from large wards that house up to 100 people and put in small cells
housing one or three prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the new cell system will put an end to
riots, hostage-takings and hunger strikes which frequently plague
Turkish prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cells are death -- we will not enter them,'' the protesters
shouted on Istanbul's fashionable Istiklal Street, the Anatolia
news agency reported. Police detained the 25 after they ignored
calls to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners belonging to Kurdish and Islamic groups often run
their own wards like indoctrination centers.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say torture is common in Turkish prisons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1008 </TRAILER>
