<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Bomber: I Regret Killings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- An Irish Republican Army bomber
who killed nine shoppers in 1993 said in an interview published
Saturday that the deaths were an accident he regrets.
</P>
<P>
   But Sean Kelly, who helped plant a bomb in a fish shop in the
mostly Protestant Shankill Road in October 1993, told the weekly
North Belfast News that he, too, was a victim of Northern Ireland's
''troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly told the newspaper that he had intended to kill leaders of
the Protestant paramilitary group the Ulster Defense Association,
whom he believed were meeting above the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that innocent people died is something I will have to
live with for the rest of my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to accept the families of those people who were killed
in the explosion will never forgive me. But it honestly was an
accident and if I could do anything to change what happened,
believe me, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's accomplice, Thomas Begley, was killed when the bomb they
were planting exploded prematurely. Kelly lost the sight in one eye
and the power in his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are those who will say I have no right to talk
about victims, but everyone has suffered, including those of us who
have been to jail,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lost my close friend Thomas Begley that day. Like the other
people who died in the bomb, he was a mother's son too.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all victims, we have all suffered, but I just hope and
pray that it is now at an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who says he now supports Northern Ireland's peace
process, was freed from the Maze prison last month as part of an
early-release program linked to the province's 1998 peace
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
