<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Rebels Kill 6 Indian Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- A Pakistan-based rebel group claimed that
two of its fighters stormed an Indian army camp in Kashmir early
Saturday and killed six soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The shootout continued for several hours in the Sarankot camp,
300 miles southwest of Srinagar, said Abu Dalaha, a spokesman for
the Lashkar-e-Tayabba, who called The Associated Press in Srinagar.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment by the Indian army headquarters
in Srinagar.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, suspected militants lobbed two hand grenades in
downtown Srinagar, police said. The first attack wounded a security
guard and two civilians near Gandhi College. In the second, outside
a mosque, suspected guerrillas threw a hand grenade at a police
jeep, seriously wounding six, including four civilians. There was
no claim of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks came as Indian government officials and the
commanders of the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, the main rebel group,
scheduled a second meeting to discuss steps to strengthen a
cease-fire agreement in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir, a former princely state, is divided between Pakistan
and India and has been the cause of two wars between them since the
British rule ended in the subcontinent in 1947. Both the countries
lay claim to a united Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen declared the three-month
cease-fire on July 24, more than a dozen other militant groups have
vowed to continue fighting the Indian forces. The groups want
Kashmir either to merge with Pakistan or gain independence from
India.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, meanwhile, urged India on Saturday to hold three-way
talks involving New Delhi, Islamabad and Kashmiri leaders.
According to the state-run Associated Press of Pakistan, the
foreign minister said the militants' demands for talks with India
is ''logical,'' and in line with U.N. resolutions recognizing
Pakistan and India as the two major parties to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Pakistan of training and arming the militants -- a
charge Islamabad denies -- and has not wanted to include Pakistan in
any talks on the future of Kashmir, where more than 25,000 people
have been killed in fighting since 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
