<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels: 45 Solidiers Killed  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rebels in the northern Congo said Saturday
they repulsed attacks by government forces backed by combat jets
and heavy weapons, killing 45 government troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Congolese Liberation Movement, one of three rebel groups
which have waged a two-year civil war against the government of
President Laurent Kabila, said its losses were light, with just two
killed since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Olivier Kamitatu said in a satellite telephone call
that rebel lines about 560 miles northeast of the capital,
Kinshasa, had held off attacks by government troops, which
bombarded them with heavy weapons loaded on gunboats on the Oubangi
River. He said the government also received support from Zimbabwean
troops, which struck rebel positions with Russian-made Sukhoi-25
and Antonov aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of the rebel claims, and
the Congolese government blamed the rebels for provoking the
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion against Kabila broke out in this central African
country, formerly called Zaire, in August 1998. The rebels accuse
the Congolese president of corruption and of harboring Hutu
militias that fled Rwanda after committing genocide there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A cease-fire was signed in July 1999 by Kabila and his allies --
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and by Rwanda and Uganda, which are
backing the rebels. The rebels signed a month later.
</P>
<P>
   But fighting continues, with Kabila blocking the deployment of
unarmed U.N. military observers and troops to protect them, and all
sides accusing each other of violations. Weeks of clashes in the
northern Congo have forced tens of thousands of refugees into
neighboring Republic of Congo and the Central African Republic,
according to the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Congolese government said earlier this week it considered
the 1999 agreement dead so long as Rwandan and Ugandan troops
continue to occupy the eastern half of Congo. Both countries said
they would withdraw only after U.N. troops deploy and the Rwandan
Hutu militia is disarmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
