<DOCNO> APW20000805.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contest for governor center stage at New Jersey's GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) - The New Jersey delegates to the
Republican National Convention last week worked and were worked on
as the party sorted out the process of selecting a new governor.
</P>
<P>
   Governor, not president.
</P>
<P>
   The televised version of the Philadelphia convention adulated a
nominee for president despite the fact George W. Bush ended the
real suspense five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey delegates at the Cherry Hill Hilton had some
suspense: Who can win what is for the moment a three-way race to
replace Gov. Christie Whitman after next year?
</P>
<P>
   First comes the June 5 primary. Positioning is underway, as
Democrats have demonstrated in the last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican lineup:
</P>
<P>
   - Senate President Donald DiFrancesco was credited by delegates
with being the most diligent during the convention with endless
small meetings and restaurant outings to cajole GOP officials.
</P>
<P>
   - Assembly Speaker Jack Collins was seen at the major functions,
but worked his charms at less visible receptions in his hotel suite
throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   - Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler, viewing himself as outside
the GOP mainstream, acted outside the hotel itself. He staged a
shadow convention for three nights at a downtown Philadelphia
auditorium, a costly affair with buses bringing in supporters from
virtually every county over three nights, but few convention
delegates. Jack Kemp, Newt Gingrich and Steve Forbes gave speeches.
</P>
<P>
   - Former Gov. Thomas Kean was as busy denying he intended to run
as others were busy circulating rumors that he might do so.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco said, ''Yeah, sure I was lobbying, meeting people.''
But he downplayed it. ''You don't want to do too much to draw away
from Bob Franks,'' the Republican candidate for U.S. Senate this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''And don't forget, this was supposed to be about George Bush,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hunterdon County chairman Henry Kuhl said DiFrancesco ''had a
very good week. He has such a nice, laid-back style but he doesn't
seem to run out of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl, whose county could be decisive, said he was not committed.
</P>
<P>
   John Bennett, who hopes to replace DiFrancesco as Senate
president, was working overtime last week to build up funding
commitments for the Senate GOP's fund-raising account.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1993 law, the legislative leaders control these
accounts, doling out cash to Senate Republicans in contested races.
Political analyst Jim McQueeny said such control gives Senate
presidents enormous influence, making it unlikely DiFrancesco or
Bennett - his second-in-command - will face much internal
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Tom Wilson, who has volunteered to help DiFrancesco,
said, ''Collins? Where was he? I don't think he was doing much at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Schundler said his shadow convention accomplished what he had
hoped. ''I am doing well as an outsider. People know who I am, and
those who attended this convention know I am in this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco gave Schundler his due for his effort but added, ''I
don't know, was it good? I didn't get over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be positive about it. Bret Schundler will be Bret
Schundler. He will try to attack us in a different way,'' he said.
''I don't think that he will be a threat in any way to where I want
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Jack Rafferty was worried about a divisive primary
hurting the party in 2001 for the nomination for governor. He
thinks Republicans should consolidate their strength against
Democrats, who are sure to launch a major effort to win the post.
</P>
<P>
   One sure candidate, Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey, ran a close
race against Whitman in 1997. He demonstrated his organizational
skills last week by outfoxing U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli in the
contest for county endorsements, causing Torricelli to drop out two
weeks after he dropped in.
</P>
<P>
   Rafferty would be pleased to see DiFrancesco consolidate support
like McGreevey has done. ''Anyone who tells you a primary doesn't
cause problems, they're wrong. There are rifts that will never be
healed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allies of the winners get a chance at government appointments,
while allies of the losers are passed over and don't soon forget
it. ''The first ones on board, they get the good jobs. The people
who came later, they get good government,'' Rafferty quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate William Gormley disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The party will be fine. We come from a very strong base of
accomplishment,'' said the Atlantic County state senator who was
himself seen as flirting with a run for governor. Gormley had a
strong second-place finish to Franks in the Republican primary for
U.S. Senate two months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 1142 </TRAILER>
