<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired cop drowns when boat flips on Lake Ontario  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A retired police officer drowned when his
boat flipped over on Lake Ontario as he attempted to escape
3-foot-high waves, but his former partner was rescued after hanging
on for an hour to the overturned craft.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murray, 60, a 20-year Rochester police veteran who
retired in 1985, and Kenneth Roblee, 52, whose police career ended
in 1969, were dragging an anchor to slow the boat from drifting as
they fished off Fair Haven beach Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When high waves started to fill the bottom of the boat with
water, they started the engine to head back to shore. Once they
started moving, water rushed to the rear of the boat, causing the
stern to sink and the boat to flip over.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was thrown about 15 feet into the water and drowned,
authorities said. Roblee, who was rescued by a boater, was treated
for hypothermia at a hospital in Newark, east of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   In their retirement years, the men sometimes operated a sandwich
stand - most recently at the Park Avenue festival in Rochester last
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
