<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Writer Detained  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- A liberal Iranian writer and cleric was
detained Saturday for attending a controversial Berlin conference
on Iran, his son said.
</P>
<P>
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency confirmed the arrest
of Hassan Yousefi Eshkevari, saying he was taken to Tehran's Evin
prison for investigation on security charges.
</P>
<P>
   Eshkevari's son, Ruhollah, 22, said his father was detained at
his home hours after returning to Iran for the first time since he
attended the conference in Berlin in April.
</P>
<P>
   ''Security forces in plain clothes searched our home for two
hours. They confiscated some books and papers, and even my personal
computer,'' Ruhollah said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference received wide publicity in Iran and was condemned
by conservatives as television footage showed women dancing and
Iranian exiles making speeches against the government. Iran's
Islamic laws do not permit women to dance in public.
</P>
<P>
   Several other delegates to the conference were detained on their
return to Iran. Some, including two women, have been released.
However, Akbar Ganji, a leading journalist opposed to Iran's
hard-liners, remains in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Eshkevari is charged with acting against national security and
publishing articles that defamed Iranian officials and criticized
the government, the official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   As Eshkevari is a cleric, he will be tried by a Special Clergy
Court once the investigation is completed, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest is seen as part of the ongoing power struggle between
reformist supporters of President Mohammad Khatami and hard-liners
who use their control of the judiciary to impede the liberal
movement.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the authorities closed a weekly satirical magazine,
Tavana, accusing it of publishing ''defamatory articles against
officials,'' the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 22nd publication to be closed since the hard-liners
began a sweeping crackdown on the press in April.
</P>
<P>
   Eshkevari had remained in Europe after the conference to do
research and give lectures on Iran, his son said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
