<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man sentenced to 95 years for killing senior citizen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - A 33-year-old Long Branch man was
sentenced to 95 years in prison for murdering his 72-year-old
friend by beating him to death with a hammer after the older man
refused to give him money to buy crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's sentencing, Donyelle Locust insisted on his
innocence and claimed that detectives lied on the witness stand and
had coerced him into a detailed confession.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Amison, a retired Marine sergeant and union official, was
found bludgeoned to death at his Asbury Park home after he refused
to give Locust some cash on Feb. 11, 1999, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Locust had borrowed about $100 from Amison
earlier in the day, but apparently wanted more. When Amison refused
the second request, Locust waited until the older man had gone to
sleep and used a hammer from the house to strike him repeatedly in
the head. Locust then stole several items of jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Locust was friends with the man and did odd jobs for
him.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Locust in June of murder, robbery, theft and
possession of a weapon for an unlawful purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Friday's hearing, Amison's nephew, James Emery, read
a letter to the courtroom that directly addressed the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Locust, you and you alone know that you killed Joe Amison,
and you knew exactly what you were doing,'' Emery said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Patricia Del Bueno Cleary sentenced Locust
to 75 years for the murder and 20 years for the robbery. He must
serve at least 80 percent of that - or about 80 years - before he
is eligible for parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
