<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists: End Iraq Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
By CHERYL WITTENAUER
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. G. Simon Harak was a professor of ethics until a 1997
trip to Iraq convinced him that a greater moral urgency demanded
his attention.
</P>
<P>
   He quit the faculty of Fairfield University in Connecticut and
now works full time in a growing ''people's movement'' to end
economic sanctions that the United Nations imposed on Iraq on Aug.
6, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the movement comprises dozens of groups, assembling this
weekend in Washington for a National Mobilization to End the
Sanctions Against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors range from three of the nation's oldest peace groups --
Fellowship of Reconciliation, Pax Christi USA and the American
Friends Service Committee -- to the American Muslim Council.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-sanctions movement includes Gulf War veterans and spans
most faiths and ages, college students and 20-somethings to
gray-haired veterans of the 1960s anti-war movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teaching ethics was great, but I made the choice,'' said
Harak, a 52-year-old Jesuit priest. ''It was a step in faith. Jesus
himself would find the sanctions intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years earlier in Chicago, a handful of peace
activists who had worked together for years to protest nuclear
arms, U.S. military involvement in Central America and the Persian
Gulf War had reached the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, a call came from Chuck Quilty, a 58-year-old
former chemical engineer from Rock Island, Ill., who quit his job
at a weapons plant 30 years earlier as an act of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Quilty was gathering his friends to find a way to end the
sanctions, which the United Nations imposed four days after
President Saddam Hussein sent Iraqi troops into neighboring Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq lost a quick war to a U.S.-led coalition in early 1991, but
sanctions were continued to force Saddam to comply with terms of
the truce demanding destruction of his weapons of mass destruction.
Many hoped the sanctions also would lead the Iraqis to oust Saddam,
but activists contend they have managed only to strangle Iraq's
economy and kill an untold number of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Quilty's meeting in peace activist Kathy Kelly's Chicago
apartment was the catalyst for an anti-sanctions group, Voices in
the Wilderness -- ''voices for children in a wilderness of
compassion'' -- and the spur for a movement to end the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Voices has led more than 30 delegations of U.S.
citizens to Iraq to witness effects of the sanctions. Their tours
include visits to pediatric wards of dying children and inoperative
water treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF says the number of infant and child deaths in Iraq has
doubled in the decade since the sanctions began.
</P>
<P>
   Strict trade sanctions are being kept in place, primarily by the
United States and Britain, until U.N. inspectors certify that Iraq
is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is allowed to sell oil under a U.N.-approved program. To
prevent diversion of proceeds to Saddam's military or other
unintended recipients, they go to a U.N. fund for food, medicine
and other essential goods and modernize Iraq's oil facilities.
Critics, including some humanitarian workers in Iraq, say it falls
far short of Iraq's needs, and some critical supplies are forbidden
by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials at the United Nations ''don't foresee changing
the sanctions regime at any point in the near future,'' said Mary
Ellen Glynn, spokeswoman for U. N. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke.
''It's within (Saddam) Hussein's capacity to feed his people
through the oil-for-food program.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the anti-sanctions movement's most optimistic adherents
believe they will end soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are moral citizens first. To those who blame Saddam, I say
we're not responsible for the things Saddam does. We are
responsible if the actions of our government keep Iraqi children
from food and clean water,'' said Doug Hostetter, international
secretary of the Fellowship of Reconciliation, which plans soon to
deliver water chlorinators to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Mobilization to End the Sanctions Against Iraq:
http://www.endthewar.org 
http://www.state.gov/www/policy--remarks/2000/000802--welch-scheffer--i
raq.html
</P>
<P>
   Voices in the Wilderness: http://www.nonviolence.org/vitw 
http://www.state.gov/www/policy--remarks/2000/000802--welch-scheffer--i
raq.html
</P>
