<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIA head says he will step down before Eastern Pequot ruling  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORTH STONINGTON, Conn. (AP) - The head of the federal Bureau of
Indian Affairs plans to leave that job before there is a final
decision on federal recognition for the Eastern Pequot and
Paucatuck Eastern Pequot tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gover has come under fire from state Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal and the leaders of the towns surrounding the
tribes' joint reservation. They claim the BIA's preliminary
decision to grant one or both tribes recognition was tainted by a
conflict of interest on the part of Gover, who once served as an
attorney for the Golden Hill Paugusetts, another Connecticut tribe
that is seeking recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Gover told the Norwich Bulletin that the final ruling on the
Eastern Pequot and Paucatuck's bids is likely more than a year away
and he intends to step down when the Clinton administration ends in
January.
</P>
<P>
   He said town officials in Ledyard, North Stonington and Preston
need to stop criticizing him and become more involved in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't know if the tribes are even going to be recognized
at the end of the day,'' Gover said. ''It seems to me their money
would be spent better addressing the merits of the petitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gover also said he believes it would be a ''waste'' of money for
the towns to file a lawsuit against the BIA and the Department of
the Interior over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process has been challenged many times and the authority
of the Bureau has been upheld many times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   North Stonington First Selectman Nicholas Mullane said Friday
while legal action would be unfortunate, town leaders believe
they've exhausted every other available avenue. Guy Martin, one of
the towns' Washington attorneys, said Friday the lawsuit would ask
that the tribes' proposed positive findings be withdrawn because
the BIA process is fundamentally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Gover suggested the towns apply to extend the 180-day comment
period to have more time to offer feedback on the tribes'
applications. If they don't, their options are limited, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comment period closes Sept. 27. Then the tribes have at
least 60 days to respond before the BIA sets the final
determination date.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from the towns and tribes will meet with BIA staff at a
public meeting Tuesday and Wednesday in Washington to discuss the
recognition process. State Attorney General Richard Blumenthal also
is scheduled to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Gover said there's very little unusual about the Easterns' and
Paucatucks' applications, except the level of resistance from
neighboring towns.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much the towns criticize, whomever rules on the
Easterns' and Paucatucks' bids will decide on the facts, not
emotion, Gover said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think anyone sitting in my chair will evaluate the decision
regardless of these accusations,'' Gover said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
