<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State, local police team up to fight Internet crime against kids  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a ninth-floor room of a Dallas hotel, Katie Tarbox first came
face-to-face with her online predator.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1995. The then-13-year-old New Canaan, Conn., resident
had arranged to meet ''Mark'' - a 41-year-old California man -
after months of Internet chat, e-mail exchanges and phone
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   She thought the Texas encounter, planned around an eighth-grade
swim meet, would be an innocent get-together between two friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mark'' had other plans. He had kissed and touched Tarbox
before her mother and swim coaches, warned by Tarbox's teammate,
came knocking on the door.
</P>
<P>
   As Tarbox recounts in her recently released book, ''Katie.com,''
the man was really Francis John Kufrovich. Federal investigations
later revealed that Kufrovich had pursued and had sex with other
girls and boys, and had downloaded child pornography onto his home
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Tarbox, now 18, said no one ever warned her about online child
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought I would ever be at risk for something like
this,'' she said in a telephone interview. ''That was the mindset I
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, law enforcement officials in Connecticut and
across the country are stepping in to change that.
</P>
<P>
   State and local law enforcement agencies are working on programs
to educate children, parents and teachers about who is lurking in
cyberspace. They fear not only those who lure children into
meetings, but those who download and send child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big problem,'' said Monique Mattei, an attorney and
planning specialist with the state police Computer Crimes Unit.
''The online stuff is particularly fertile ground for attempting to
engage minors in sexual activities and pedophiles in general,
because it's where kids like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The state last year used a $300,000 federal grant to create an
Internet Crimes Against Children Task Force. Its purposes: to
investigate online activity, develop training programs for local
and state police and promote online safety education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in September, Mattei said, the task force will
introduce Internet-based lessons to fourth- through sixth-graders
at five schools in Connecticut. The pilot program will include an
interactive demonstration. Mattei said the two, 40-minute lessons
should be in place statewide by the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also is working on an educational Web site where
parents and children can get information on avoiding online
predators.
</P>
<P>
   And the unit recruits local police officers for a minimum of a
years' worth of ''top notch'' computer crime training, Mattei said.
Officers from Hamden and Central Connecticut State University are
already working with the state police; officers from South Windsor
and Milford were slated to start this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Online anonymity gives criminals a sense of security, said David
Finkelhor, director of the Crimes Against Children Research Center
at the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ''It creates an environment where people feel at liberty to do
illegal things. We need to have law enforcement there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its first year of operation - August 1998-99 - Connecticut's
Computer Crimes Unit handled 103 cases. Of those, 25 percent dealt
with child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Between August 1999 and February 2000, Mattei said, the agency
took on 270 new cases, three quarters if them involving child
pornography or exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-based National Center for Missing &AMP; Exploited
Children estimates there were 785 ''traveler'' cases nationwide in
1999 - incidents where a child or adult traveled to meet physically
with someone first encountered on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the FBI has dedicated several hundred agents to
Internet crimes cases against children since 1994, said Peter
Gulotta Jr., a special agent in the Baltimore office. Fifteen of
the FBI's 58 field offices have task forces that specialize in that
kind of crime, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several related bills are before Congress, ranging from stiffer
penalties for ''travelers'' to a national training facility for
policing Internet crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Some Connecticut police departments have their own Internet
crime initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Derby Detective Sgt. Gerald Narowski gives presentations at area
high schools to educate parents and teachers about the dangers of
cyberspace. Narowski said he shows adults how easy it is to pop
into a chat room and strike up a conversation. Within 10 minutes,
he said, the talk usually becomes sexually explicit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority of the parents were oblivious to the threats out
there,'' he said. ''They had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Narowski said he teaches people to work with the Internet, not
fear it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that scary a place if you know what's out there,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   In Milford, police Chief Thomas Flaherty said he plans to create
a new Internet crime unit as part of his detectives' bureau, to be
staffed with several officers from his 109-member department.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a priority,'' he said. ''It's the future of crime. The
volume of these kinds of cases exceeds the ability of a local
department to investigate them.''
</P>
<P>
   New Britain Detective James Wardwell - who works in the unit
that fights other crimes against children - is involved in a case
that started with his own online investigation. Wardwell wound up
in contact with a predator who thought the officer was underage.
</P>
<P>
   The case, he said, is now in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every single police agency, sooner or later, is going to have
to deal with computer-related crime,'' Wardwell said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy. Mattei said the state's investigations are
labor-intensive and the jurisdiction issues in cyberspace are often
confusing. Of the cases the state's taken on, she said, many remain
open.
</P>
<P>
   ''It drags out,'' Mattei said. ''It seems like forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarbox agreed that the court process can be frustrating, often
because there are no precedents. More than two years after the
encounter, Kufrovich was sentenced to 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eighteen months is not going to cut it for Frank when they
knew about a serious history,'' Tarbox said.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, her focus is on preparing for her freshman year at
the University of Pennsylvania. She's also working on another
personal memoir about what it's like to be 18.
</P>
<P>
   And Tarbox is still online, although she avoids chat rooms and
instant messages from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great tool to aid in everyday life,'' she said, of the
Internet. ''But when I signed on at 13, I thought it was a meeting
place.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: - http://www.KatieT.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.missingkids.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.unh.edu/ccrc/index.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fbi.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
