<HEADLINE> Judge dismisses last count of Williams lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A state Superior Court judge has dismissed
what little remained of a $21.8 million discrimination lawsuit by
the ousted head of the New Jersey State Police.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Judith Yaskin on Friday dismissed a count in Carl
Williams' lawsuit that alleged that Gov. Christie Whitman conspired
with former Attorney General Peter Verniero and her director of
communications to ''libel and defame'' Williams by implying he was
a racist.
</P>
<P>
   Yaskin also dismissed a claim by Williams that he had been
defamed by state Assemblyman LeRoy Jones Jr. Earlier, she had
dismissed a similar claim against The Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Williams' lawsuit was dismissed in July.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Williams claimed that the governor wanted him to resign
in retaliation for published remarks he made linking minorities
with drug trafficking and discriminated against him because she
wanted to appoint a younger, black man.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman pressed for Williams to resign in February 1999 after
The Star-Ledger published an interview in which he made comments
about police practicing racial profiling, or stopping motorists
based on their race.
</P>
</TEXT>
