<DOCNO> APW20000805.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbia's Opposition Divided  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The leader of Serbia's largest
opposition party said Saturday his group may reverse its decision
to boycott presidential elections but run its own candidate rather
than back one expected to be nominated by the rest of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The entry of a second opposition candidate in the race could
hand President Slobodan Milosevic victory in the Sept. 24 polls.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, said his
party would meet Sunday to make the final decision on challenging
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic said he expected the party to nominate the opposition
mayor of Belgrade, Vojislav Mihailovic, as its presidential
candidate. He said Mihailovic, a senior figure in the Serbian
Renewal Movement, should be the only opposition candidate to face
Milosevic, who so far is the only declared candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the fractured Serbian opposition movement is
expected to support Vojislav Kostunica, leader of the small,
center-right Democratic Party of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, however, said Kostunica ''is someone who is so
secluded, who never travels abroad and who would basically continue
Milosevic's policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opposition parties had been urging the Serbian Renewal
Movement to abandon its threatened boycott, saying the election
offered the best chance to rid the country of Milosevic after years
of ethnic wars, economic devastation and international isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's party had said any election supervised by the
Milosevic government would be neither free nor fair. However, other
opposition leaders are reluctant to rally around a candidate allied
with the mercurial Draskovic, who served as a Yugoslav deputy prime
minister until he was fired during the 1999 NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another opposition leader, Zoran Djindjic, told B2-92 Radio that
Draskovic was trying to promote his own party's candidate and to
take away votes from a united opposition. ''Thus, he helps
Milosevic,'' Djindjic said.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic denied he was collaborating with Milosevic ''while I
am still recovering from my injuries inflicted by Milosevic's
killers. May God give them such collaboration with Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic was slightly wounded in an assassination attempt in
his summer home in Montenegrin coastal town of Budva on June 15. He
accused Milosevic of the attack, although the government has denied
any role.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Western administration in Montenegro, which along with
Serbia forms the Yugoslav federation, has also refused to take part
in the presidential election, despite an appeal from U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic denied any
pressure on him to take part in the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is pressuring Montenegro,'' Djukanovic said. ''The
views of Montenegro are relevant for the international community in
creating policies concerning southeastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Montenegrins should not worry about
''provocations launched by the Yugoslav army.'' The army, which is
loyal to Milosevic, maintains nearly 20.000 well-armed and trained
troops in Montenegro. Djukanovic can rely on a 15.000-member
paramilitary police force.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that the Belgrade authorities and their puppets in
Montenegro are launching regarding the republic's role at the
forthcoming balloting is a mere lie, an expression of allegiance
psychology and anti-Montenegrin hysteria,'' Djukanovic told the
newspaper Vijesti.
</P>
<P>
   He said Montenegro ''has the power and motive and the citizens
to protect its freedom and dignity if necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
