<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Seeks EU Ties  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Despite differences within the government
over European Union expansion, Austria's foreign minister is
calling for a ''strategic partnership'' between Austria and Eastern
European countries seeking to join the EU to promote the interests
of smaller states.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should promote a strategic partnership with the states of
central and eastern Europe because we have common interests,''
Foreign Minister Benita Ferrero-Waldner said in an interview
published Saturday by the Salzburger Nachrichten newspaper. ''I
have made this alliance my foreign policy priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner's comments contrast sharply with statements made
during last year's election campaign by the far-right Freedom Party
of Joerg Haider. The Freedom Party is now part of the governing
coalition along with the foreign minister's conservative Austrian
Peoples' Party.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's party finished second among the five parties in the
October election after warning Austrians that EU expansion would
threaten jobs because industry would relocate to the low-cost
countries of the former Soviet bloc.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ferrero-Waldner underscored the historical and cultural
ties between Austria and Eastern European countries, many of which
were part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. She said Austria had a
stake in the economic and political success of countries such as
Poland, Bulgaria and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one can take away this historical and also cultural
tradition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner said such a partnership was necessary to promote
the interests of small European states and serve as a counterweight
to the major powers such as Germany and France within the EU.
</P>
<P>
   Five countries -- Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Spain --
account for more than half the population in the 15-member EU.
</P>
<P>
   ''There must be equality with all other partner states,''
Ferrero-Waldner said. ''At the same time, one must ask how a small
state in this large (European) Union can lobby the best for itself.
I believe it is through the building of this alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comments reflect a growing debate within Europe over the
future of the EU after a speech in May by German Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer, who said the vision of a united Europe from 50
years ago should be carried to its logical end with a European
Federation led by an executive branch and two houses of legislature
codified in a European constitution.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone isn't ready to go that far right now, a ''core
group'' of countries should make the first move and the rest can
join later, he said. That triggered a backlash among smaller EU
countries which fear such a union would be dominated by Germany and
France.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner said she could foresee the European Union
developing into a ''United States of Europe,'' underpinned by a
European constitution. However, she called this a ''utopian idea''
and said such a move would require a continent-wide political
debate about what ''would be decided on a regional, a national and
at a European level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
