<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helen Quinn, Met's Queen of Standees, dies  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - The singing has stopped for the Queen of Standees.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Quinn, so dubbed as the infamous, self-appointed manager
of the Metropolitan Opera's standing-room tickets line for 32
years, has died. She was 76.
</P>
<P>
   It's ''the only system of its kind in the world,'' the retired
keypunch operator once said with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday morning, rain or shine, hot or cold, she arrived
at the opera house at about 6 a.m. Equipped with a bullhorn and a
clipboard, Quinn took charge of the willing crowd of opera buffs
who came to buy that week's allotment of standing-room tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the head of the line, she scribbled down each
person's name on a list. And if they got out of line, or failed to
respond, she would turn on her gruff schoolmarm manner - with a
wink - and get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quiet, back there!'' Quinn warned when the buzz of
conversation interrupted her task.
</P>
<P>
   Then the fans were free to trickle off to breakfast, to get some
more sleep - to do anything, in short, but wait in line.
</P>
<P>
   They had to be back by about 9 a.m. - the box office opens at 10
a.m. - to pay attention while she barked out their names and handed
out numbered slips of paper. And if someone cut into the line, ''I
pounce.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to get a $12 spot upstairs in the house or a $16
space behind the velvet orchestra seats - one of the 175
standing-room tickets available for each performance.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who grew up in Port Chester, N.Y., had been doing this
without pay every Saturday since 1968 - since she decided to stop
the bickering one day while she herself was standing in line at the
Met.
</P>
<P>
   She saw her first opera, Mozart's ''The Magic Flute,'' while
still in high school in 1943, and became such a fan that she
eventually moved to an apartment on West 57th Street near the Met.
</P>
<P>
   She had three hobbies: opera, horse racing and the Yankees. In
that order.
</P>
<P>
   But she never worked for the Met, which nevertheless appreciated
her service and wrote her a letter to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn died Wednesday at her Manhattan apartment, of food
poisoning, said Josephine Rowe, a friend who promises to continue
running the standing-room line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 1434 </TRAILER>
