<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio attacks Clintons over marriage penalty veto  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - ''Flabbergasted'' by the president's
long-distance veto of the Republican-sponsored tax cut for married
couples Saturday, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio accused the president and
Hillary Rodham Clinton of being out of touch with New York
families, the average American, and reality.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who is running for U.S. Senate against the first lady,
criticized her for not being an advocate for the tax cut, which
President Clinton vetoed before a morning round of golf on the
Massachusetts resort island of Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ''She certainly has had an opportunity over these last eight
years to be an advocate for it, to support, to speak out for it,''
Lazio said in Buffalo after addressing the Vietnam Veterans of
America's biennial National Leadership Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's remarkable about today is it just shows you how out of
touch both of the Clintons are with the average New Yorker, with
the average American, that you can be in the middle of a golf game
at some fancy golf club on Martha's Vineyard, be in the process of
raising a half million dollars in soft, unregulated money to pour
into a campaign in a state that you have very little attachment to,
and then at the same time veto a bill that helps provide some basic
tax relief, some tax fairness, for America's working families,''
the Republican congressman said. ''I just think it shows an
incredible lack of attachment with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide for the first lady's campaign said Lazio's support of
the marriage penalty measure illustrated an important difference
between the Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that Congressman Lazio supports a risky tax scheme
that would squander our surplus,'' campaign spokesman Howard
Wolfson said. ''Hillary Clinton believes we need to use the surplus
to pay down the debt and preserve Medicare and Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the candidates' volley over soft money continued
with a letter from Lazio campaign manager Bil Dal Col to his
counterpart in the Clinton camp, Bill de Blasio.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lazio, claiming millions of unregulated dollars have
been poured into Clinton's Senate race to produce negative ads,
said he wouldn't use soft money in his campaign if Clinton didn't.
The Clinton campaign responded by pointing out that advisers to the
first lady had said in May that she would consider renouncing soft
money if her opponent did the same.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's letter, Dal Col again urged Clinton to stop
soliciting soft money contributions, and also to return existing
money and to call on outside groups to stop running attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''Upon receipt of your letter,'' Dal Col said, ''our campaign
will send you a similar letter of intent, call on all outside
groups to refrain from interfering in the campaign, and will agree
not to open any soft money accounts of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Buffalo, Lazio received a warm reception from
members of the Vietnam Veterans of America in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have to tell all of you I'm in the toughest fight of
my political life right now and I could use your support,'' he
said, ''and because nobody knows more about a tough fight than
Vietnam vets I'm proud to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization does not endorse candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio used a 15-minute address to criticize the Clinton
administration for military cuts, which he said have put the lives
of military personnel at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have my unwavering commitment that I will fight to restore
the strength to our armed forces and respect to our veterans,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several New York veterans indicated their support for Lazio was
as much about being anti-Clinton as pro-Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad that a person like Bill Clinton, a draft dodger, will
get better medical care than any veteran,'' said Dick Chipchak, a
Republican who served in the Navy from 1964-68.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, Lazio will embark on an out-of-state
fund-raising campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
