<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man convicted of conspiring to fix races won't go to jail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - A harness driver convicted of conspiring
to fix races won't serve any jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Patricia Del Bueno Cleary sentenced Richard
Wojcio to five years probation on Friday and imposed a $7,500 fine.
Wojcio also was ordered to perform 500 hours of community service,
which he has already completed.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing comes after a state appellate court ordered a new
hearing for Wojcio, who originally received a sentence of 180 days
in Monmouth County Jail, 500 hours of community service and five
years probation.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court in July upheld Wojcio's conviction, but
struck down two aggravating factors Cleary used when sentencing the
once-prominent harness racer in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wojcio apologized in court before he was sentenced a second
time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry to the betting public. I'm sorry to the harness
racing industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney described the hardships the driver - who won 405
races and more than $2.4 million in purse money in 1995 - has faced
since his arrest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Plaza said Wojcio's problems after the arrest should
deter others from conspiring to fix races. Wojcio was banished from
the raceway, sold his house and now lives in a one-bedroom
apartment. Employers have turned Wojcio down for several jobs,
including one as a delivery truck driver. He now paints houses.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General William Gicking argued that Wojcio
betrayed honest harness drivers who struggle to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to make those who resort to this type of conduct know
that the price is far too high,'' Gicking said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary agreed that Wojcio's life ''has been virtually
destroyed'' by the conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
