<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Fox To Go to S. America  </HEADLINE>
By TRACI CARL
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Throughout his campaign and since his
election as Mexico's next president, Vicente Fox has pushed for
more free trade.
</P>
<P>
   His first diplomatic trip as president-elect will be no
different, with Fox traveling to Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay to
discuss an agreement with the Mercosur trading bloc. He will also
visit Chile, meeting with leaders and opposition groups in all four
countries.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Fox became the first opposition presidential
candidate to defeat a member of Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which has been in power since its creation in
1929.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his support for free trade follows the lead of his
predecessor, President Ernesto Zedillo, who negotiated many trade
deals, including agreements with Israel, the European Union and
several countries in Central America. Zedillo also talked of an
agreement with Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea is that Mexico has to sign free trade agreements with
everybody in sight,'' said Sidney Weintraub, of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies, a Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico fears it is too highly dependent on the U.S. economy,
Weintraub said. It has looked to expand into other markets to
protect itself from an economic downturn by its neighbor to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Trade pacts have fueled exports, helping Mexico rally from its
1995 economic crisis. Yet critics have accused the government of
helping only those prepared for the global economy, leaving behind
people who weren't ready to compete and exacerbating income
disparities.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, however, has fully embraced free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after his election, he began lobbying for the
eventual expansion of the North American Free Trade Agreement into
a common market similar to that of the European Union -- including
the free movement of workers between Mexico, the United States and
Canada. The idea is likely to face opposition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, has also promoted the idea of
expanding the four-nation trading bloc known as Mercosur, which
includes Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings Monday in Chile, Fox will discuss a possible
Mercosur agreement with leaders in Argentina on Tuesday, followed
by trips to Brazil and Uruguay later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president-elect won't be able to sign any
agreements until he takes over the presidency Dec. 1, leading
Weintraub to believe the trip is more about appearances than trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''My instinct is that Fox is trying to establish himself as a
big player in the hemispheric and even world scene, and these
visits have as much that in mind as they do signing agreements,''
he said. ''I assume that's the purpose: to build up his own
stature.''
</P>
<P>
   After his trip to South America, Fox will travel to Canada and
the United States, meeting Aug. 22 with Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien in Ottawa and Aug. 24 with President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to travel to Dallas to Aug. 25 to talk with Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, Gore's opponent in the presidential election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1513 </TRAILER>
