<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother wants state to pay for wrongly imprisoning mentally ill son  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STORMVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - The mother of a mentally ill man is
suing New York state for imprisoning her son after he was mistaken
for another man.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Los Angeles, where Kerry Sanders was picked up on
a park bench and soon after extradited to New York on a warrant for
prison escapee Robert Sanders, settled a suit with Mary Sanders Lee
for $290,000 for their role in the mistake. But Lee's battle to get
compensation from New York to help her ensure proper care for her
son continues five years after Kerry Sanders was released.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' two years in prison and his exoneration were reported
for the first time in today's New York Times Sunday magazine
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal began when a Los Angeles police officer found Kerry
Sanders sleeping on a park bench on Oct. 5, 1993. Sanders had been
on and off medication for paranoid schizophrenia for a few years,
and was staying alternately with family, in hospitals, and on the
street at the time.
</P>
<P>
   When the officer asked a dispatcher if there were any warrants
out for Sanders, two came back. One was for Kerry Sanders, accused
of jaywalking. The other was for Robert Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The two men shared a birth date, June 25, 1966. Both were black,
a couple inches apart in height and about 20 pounds different in
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Prison records showed that Robert Sanders was a repeat criminal
from New York who tried to kill a man over a cocaine deal in 1990
and escaped three years later while on work release at a
minimum-security prison in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Richard Bentley, said in a recent interview that
when he asked Sanders if he used any other names, he responded,
''Yes - Terry and Robert.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked him whether he was the Robert Sanders they were
looking for in New York,'' Bentley said, ''and he looked me
straight in the eye and said, 'Yes, I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   In his police report, Bentley listed only ''Terry'' under
nicknames and made no mention of the questions about New York.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the case, Kerry Sanders made alternately true and
occasionally delusional claims about his identity. Adding to the
confusion, his fingerprints were never checked. And although his
jaywalking arrest took place while Robert Sanders was in prison,
that and several other discrepancies were not pursued.
</P>
<P>
   During the two years he was in the Green Haven prison in
Dutchess County, Kerry Sanders continually told psychologists and
others that he did not know why he was there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his mother pestered police and searched skid row,
questioning homeless people and gang members trying to find her
son.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't have it in my heart that my son was dead,'' Lee said.
''If he's dead, I'm dead.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7, 1995, federal agents arrested a man waiting in a
Cleveland bus station. He was accused of dealing cocaine. Unsure of
the man's identity, the agents took fingerprints and sent them to
the F.B.I. Within hours, the Drug Enforcement Agency learned that
the prints matched those of Robert Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until authorities discovered Sanders was supposedly
sitting in a prison in New York that Kerry Sanders' fingerprints
were taken. He was quietly sent back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   New York's attorney general's office is fighting Lee's lawsuit
in Federal District Court in Manhattan. The state did not dispute
that Sanders was wrongly imprisoned, but claimed it was not liable.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne L. Strack, then-deputy commissioner for corrections, said
he was ''flabbergasted'' when he learned about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all the checks and balances that we've got, I can't
understand how it happened,'' Strack said in a deposition. ''I
mean, it's drilled in you from Day One of the job: You take an
inmate, you're responsible, you identify him. I mean - my mind goes
boggled.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the blame for the mistake was broad because
''too many things happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Sanders, now 34, has been living since March at a
supervised board-and-care residence in Los Angeles, where he has
his own room and a structured schedule, as well as psychiatric and
health care. A van takes him to counseling and classes.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sanders remains in federal prison in the Cleveland drug
case, serving a 15-year sentence, the Times reported. New York
still has a warrant out for his arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 1553 </TRAILER>
