<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechens Warn of Upcoming Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Rebel commanders urged Chechen civilians
Saturday to flee before they launch a major offensive on
Russian-held towns, while the military stepped up security at
checkpoints and administrative buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels in breakaway Chechnya have been spreading leaflets that
warn civilians to leave their homes from Saturday to Monday ''when
armed actions will be carried out'' against Russian installations
and soldiers, the military command's press center said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets have appeared in the Nozhai-Yurt region in eastern
Chechnya, which borders on the Russian republic of Dagestan. It was
unclear when the threatened attacks could begin or where civilians
were supposed to go.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders have said there could be a wave of attacks on
Sunday, which Chechen separatists regard as their independence day
because it marks the fourth anniversary of their retaking of the
capital Grozny from Russian forces in the 1994-96 war. That war
ended with Russian troops withdrawing in humiliation a few months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops re-entered Chechnya last September, and rebels
fled Grozny en masse in early February. But rebel hit-and-run
attacks and bombings continue in the city and elsewhere in the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, several Russian servicemen were injured when a
checkpoint in Grozny was attacked by rifle and mortar fire, and an
armored personnel carrier was hit by a grenade launcher, said an
official at the Russian headquarters for Chechnya, in the city of
Gudermes.
</P>
<P>
   Girding for possible attacks on Sunday, the military has
increased security at checkpoints and administrative buildings and
tightened travel restrictions on Chechnya's roads.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny's shattered streets were unusually quiet Saturday, and
there was almost none of the informal street trade that has been
the city's main commerce for months.
</P>
<P>
   Some said fears of a rebel offensive were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   An official from Grozny's civilian administration said the
militants were too fractured and diminished in number to launch a
coordinated offensive, the Interfax news agency reported. The
official, who was not named, said authorities are urging Grozny's
civilians to stay home and ignore the rebels' call to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for the rebel command who identified
himself as Alikhan told The Associated Press from central Chechnya
that the militants had no plans to try to seize Grozny on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will do it some other time, when no one expects it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian forces on Saturday carried out attacks of
their own, sending warplanes and helicopter gunships to bombard
suspected rebel targets in the Nozhai-Yurt, Vedeno and Argun
regions. Russian artillery pounded the Kurchaloi district, where a
Chechen leader, President Aslan Maskhadov, is believed to be based,
the official in Gudermes said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent troops back into Chechnya after rebels there twice
raided Dagestan a year ago and after apartment bombings in Russia
that killed 300 people. Moscow blames Chechens for the bombings, a
charge the rebels deny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1553 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
