<HEADLINE> With BC-NY--Telephone Talks, Bjt  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The issues involved in negotiations between unions
and Verizon
Communications and the potential impact of a strike:
Issues:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -The Communications Workers of America (72,500 Verizon workers)
and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers (14,700
workers) want higher pay, improved benefits, greater job security
and better working conditions. The unions also want more access to
nonunion jobs and workers in Verizon's growing wireless division,
the nation's largest. Of Verizon's 32,000 wireless workers, fewer
than 50 are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   -The unions represent operators, customer service workers and
repair workers in Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont, Massachusetts,
Rhode Island, New York, New Jersey, Delaware, Pennsylvania,
Maryland, Virginia and West Virginia, and the District of Columbia.
Potential Impact:
</P>
<P>
   -No interruption in regular telephone service or 911 emergency
service, according to Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   -No effect on wireless operations, according to Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   -Delays in repairs of local telephone service for residential
and business customers, installation, and resolving billing
questions. ''If there is an outage ... it will be a lengthy phone
outage, if there's a strike going on,'' CWA spokesman Jeff Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   -Repairs and service on long-distance would affect only Verizon
customers in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
