<HEADLINE> Democracy Forum Held in Singapore  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- Democracy advocates from Asian countries
meeting in Singapore on Saturday scoffed at the claims of some
regional leaders that political freedoms were culturally unsuited
for Asian peoples.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians -- many from opposition parties -- who gathered
for a forum on political openness in Asia rejected the so-called
''Asian values'' argument, which says Asians favor social stability
and order over individual rights like freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's this nonsense about different Asian values when it
comes to basic human rights? It is but the convenient excuse of
some Asian leaders to deny very basic human rights,'' said Martin
Lee, a member of Hong Kong's Legislative Council and chairman of
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians also criticized the argument by some Asian
leaders that political openness is a luxury, which can only be
granted after countries gain economic wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Openness creates wealth and prosperity,'' said Lim Guan Eng,
vice chairman of Malaysia's opposition Democratic Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians from Hong Kong, Malaysia, Singapore and Taiwan
gathered for the forum, which was organized by the Open Singapore
Center, a private group that promotes political openness in this
tightly controlled city-state. About 50 spectators turned up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
