<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At FDR's home, Social Security celebrates anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By REAGAN HAYNES
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) - Social Security's 65th birthday was
celebrated Saturday at the home of Franklin D. Roosevelt, the
president who brought it to life.
</P>
<P>
   Young and old gathered on a sunny stretch of lawn outside the
tan stucco and stone home to watch a re-enactment of the speech
that preceded the Aug. 14, 1935 ''fireside chat'' and bill-signing.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging 11 percent of American senior citizens live
in poverty today despite the law, the agency said that without its
benefits, the figure would be half.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's as Roosevelt said in his speech earlier, this is a
foundation for people, and it grows and changes with the times,''
Social Security Commissioner Kenneth Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said Roosevelt considered Social Security a
cornerstone of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   But when he signed that first bill to financially assist
retirees, he was viewed as a communist. On Saturday, retirees
considered his memory only with gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very fortunate to be with Social Security,'' said
Harold Goodwill, 81, who performed at the event with the Golden Age
Singers. ''With the program benefits I can really enjoy things.''
</P>
<P>
   James Roosevelt spoke about his grandfather and the program that
was part of the ''New Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Apfel said that although the number of seniors will double over
the next 20 years as people live longer, Social Security will be
there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an intergenerational system. I'm paying for my dad's
retirement and you're paying for your grandparents,'' he said.
''It's changed with the times to last 65 years, and it will be
there 65 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Maurice Hinchey praised the program that has expanded
to cover about 44 million people, paying tribute to Eleanor
Roosevelt's ''coaxing'' her husband for reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her role as my grandfather's eyes and ears, her reports to him
of ... poverty and older America, inspired him to fight the good
fight,'' James Roosevelt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
