<HEADLINE> Professor's new test format gives instant feedback  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, N.J. (AP) - Students in Mike Epstein's psychology
classes don't wonder long if they've picked the right answer on a
multiple choice test.
</P>
<P>
   With Epstein's special answer sheet, they know as soon as they
make their choice - and leave the classroom with their exam grade.
</P>
<P>
   The Rider University psychology professor claims his form is a
vast improvement over the fill-in-the-circle computer sheets that
have become common in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are lousy devices,'' he said. ''They don't really get at
what a person knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein's patented answer sheet features scratch-off boxes
similar to those on instant lottery tickets. Test-takers pick their
answer and scratch off the corresponding box.
</P>
<P>
   If their choice is correct, they'll see a star underneath the
gray box. If they're wrong, they keep guessing until they find it.
</P>
<P>
   Students get partial credit if they know enough about the topic
to guess correctly on the second or third try. And he said his
method ensures they know the correct answer immediately, instead of
waiting several days for the test to be graded.
</P>
<P>
   ''Psychologists know learning requires feedback and the speed in
which you get it matters. What do we do with standardized tests? If
you're lucky you get the test back within 48 hours and very often
the instructor doesn't give back the tests - just the answers,''
Epstein said. ''It's really ridiculous, you're not learning from
your exam.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein, who has taught at Rider since 1971, began using his
form, called ''Immediate Feedback Assessment Technique,'' or
''IF-AT,'' about three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At first it was a big adjustment for students used to filling in
circles with a No. 2 pencil. Epstein said they were reluctant to
scratch off their first answer. And they quickly learned they
couldn't change an answer if they made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ''I often heard groans in the classroom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But most students have told him they prefer his answer form to
the computer sheets, and have even asked other instructors to use
them.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein, meanwhile, has revised the test to include an
anti-cheating mechanism that prevents students from making hairline
scratches to find the star. He's also done some research that
indicates the form helps people learn.
</P>
<P>
   If a student makes a mistake on a test using a computer answer
sheet, Epstein said there's a 75 to 85 percent chance they will
provide a wrong answer on a follow-up exam. On tests where students
use the his form, they have a 60 percent chance of being correct on
the second try.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein has already sold forms to more than 20 schools
nationwide and in Canada. The Trenton school district also plans to
begin using the form this fall to help students prepare for the
state's standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   He charges about 10 cents a sheet and is trying to market the
form for licensing tests and study guides.
</P>
<P>
   David DiBattista, a psychology professor at Brock University in
Ontario, Canada, said he used the form in some courses this year.
</P>
<P>
   He likes that the test tells students the correct answer
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your evaluation form also becomes a learning opportunity for
the student,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most students he surveyed also liked the immediacy and
appreciated the partial credit.
</P>
<P>
   Their only complaint is they can't change their selection.
</P>
<P>
   ''What they did say is using the IF-AT does require a little
more thought because once you scratch you can't go back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a drawback for teachers: The test must be graded by
hand. But DiBattista claims the exams don't take long to get
through if students do the initial grading.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Connor from Binghamton University in New York also uses the
answer form in her classes.
</P>
<P>
   The form is motivational, she said, because students respond to
it like they're playing a game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he has a real winner there,'' said the psychology
professor.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Rider University
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rider.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 1655 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
