<DOCNO> APW20000805.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribunal May Be Needed for E. Timor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- The United Nations may need to set up a
war crimes tribunal to prosecute those responsible for the death
and destruction that wracked East Timor last year, the top U.N.
human rights official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner for human rights, said
that if Indonesia fails to punish the people behind the violence
that followed Timor's vote for independence in August 1999, the
United Nations may have to.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing is to bring perpetrators to
justice,'' she said after arriving in East Timor's capital Dili.
''That can either be done by courts in Indonesia or in East Timor.
Or if it is necessary it can be done by an international
tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important ... that the message goes out that there is no
impunity,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-independence militia, backed by elements in the Indonesian
military, went on a rampage after the U.N.-sponsored vote for
independence ended 24 years of Indonesian rule, killing dozens,
destroying hundreds of buildings and leaving thousands displaced.
</P>
<P>
   Order was restored only after an Australian-led peacekeeping
force arrived and Indonesian troops withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said a future tribunal should be limited to addressing
crimes committed leading up to, and immediately after, the election
in August, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments have said they would back the creation of an
international war crimes tribunal -- akin to those for the former
Yugoslavia and Rwanda -- if Indonesia's government fails to act
against military commanders responsible for the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is scheduled to spend three days in East Timor before
traveling on to Jakarta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1702 </TRAILER>
