<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hackensack cops bag 3 in fake luggage operation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - Police have bagged three men who they
say cranked out $750,000 worth of bogus Louis Vuitton purses.
</P>
<P>
   Officers raided the warehouse of the TK Trading Company Thursday
night, arresting Kwon Kim, 46, of New City, N.Y.; No Chong, 31, of
Queens, N.Y.; and Thomas Rojas, 25, also of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Each was charged with criminal simulation.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they believe Kim and Chong operated the warehouse,
which was formerly called 222 Trading, and that Rojas was an
employee.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was carried out after an 18-month investigation. Inside
the warehouse, investigators found purses, and stacks of designer
labels not attached to any merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   U.S Customs officials said the purses were imported from Korea.
To fool Customs agents inspecting the shipment, the fake Louis
Vuitton labels on the purses were covered by a sewn-on layer of
brown plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Once the bags were inside the warehouse, workers would peel off
the plastic covering, said Hackensack police Capt. Michael Morgada.
</P>
<P>
   The bogus handbags sold for $40 to $50 each, authorities said.
Real Louis Vuitton purses sell for $350 to $3,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
