<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Rights Group Sues for Permit  </HEADLINE>
By SALAH NASRAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egypt's most prominent human rights group
decided Saturday to sue the government for the right to function,
its secretary-general, Hafez Abu Saada, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian Organization for Human Rights will appeal to the
courts against a Ministry of Social Affairs decision to postpone
indefinitely a permit for the group, Abu Saada said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ministry's delay is unconstitutional and we are going to
court to challenge it,'' Abu Saada said after a meeting of the
EOHR's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the ministry said it was delaying a permit at the
request of state security officials.
</P>
<P>
   The EOHR's difficulties are seen as part of a series of moves
against government critics in recent months, including the
detention of the academic and rights activist Saad Eddin Ibrahim
and the suspension of the Islamic-oriented Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Saada said the ministry had violated the law on
associations, which says that organizations can start functioning
60 days after applying for a license if the government does not
reject their applications.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-day period for the EOHR ended on July 30, Abu Saada said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the licensing department at the Social Affairs
Ministry, Mohammed Abdel Moneim Tawfic, said Saturday that the
EOHR's application had not been turned down and the group still has
a chance to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The security (agency) wanted some clarifications and
documents,'' Tawfic said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied the government was trying to restrict the EOHR's
activities, saying ''we are only trying to protect them against
malpractice.'' He refused to say when the license was expected to
be issued.
</P>
<P>
   EOHR's requests for government permission to receive foreign and
local funds have been rejected, Abu Saada said. The group was
hampered from fundraising in Egypt because of its lack of legal
status.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday night's meeting, the trustees decided to contribute
funds from their own pockets in order to keep the organization
alive, Abu Saada said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1985, the EOHR is Egypt's first independent rights
group and remains among its most respected. It functioned without a
permit until last year when a change of legislation forced it to
apply for a license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1725 </TRAILER>
