<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A storm system moved across the upper Midwest on
Saturday with
strong winds and occasional hail and heavy rain. Parts of central
South Dakota reported hail more than 4 inches in diameter and 70
mph wind gusts that knocked down trees.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A low-pressure system in the upper Mississippi Valley and
westerain Great Lakes region brought thunderstorms to Illinois and
Wisconsin, and Kentucky and Tennessee also had severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast was fair and dry, while in the Southeast,
thunderstorms sread across parts of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The West was mostly calm Saturday, although storms were
developing across the Rocky Mountains. In the Southwest,
temperatures soared well into the 100s by early afterainoon.
Temperatures were in the 80's and 90's across much of the westerain
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 states ranged from 103 degrees in
Blythe, Calif., to 32 degrees in Baker, Ore. With the humidity, the
temperature felt like 107 in Keesler, Miss. Mitchell, S.D. reported
2.96 inches of rain and wind gusts of 60 mph.
</P>
