<HEADLINE> France To Destroy Soybean Fields  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The French government has decided to destroy 115
acres of soybeans in southern France containing genetically
modified seeds, officials announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other crops, genetically modified soybean is not
authorized in France.
</P>
<P>
   The seven owners of the fields, located in the Bouches-du-Rhone
region around Marseille and the nearby Herault region, are to be
compensated, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   France is opposed to most genetically modified, or GM, products.
However, authorities recently decided against uprooting 11,100
acres of cornfields in southwest France scattered with genetically
modified corn.
</P>
<P>
   Certain types of GM tobacco and corn are authorized for planting
in France.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian prime minister, meanwhile, decided to suspend the
sale of four types of genetically modified corn as a
''precautionary measure,'' although his health minister had
approved the products, the Milan daily Il Giornale reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Giuliano Amato's Cabinet approved the suspension
at a meeting Friday that was not attended by Health Minister
Umberto Veronesi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1836 </TRAILER>
