<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Recovers From Stroke  </HEADLINE>
By HOPE YEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Doctors on Saturday said former President
Gerald Ford had probably completely recovered from the small stroke
he had suffered, and they performed surgery to correct an abscess
in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's tongue had been painfully swollen for several days, but
it quickly returned to normal size after Saturday's operation, said
Dr. Richard Hayden, chief of the ear, nose and throat department at
Hahnemann University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''His comfort level is markedly improved and his speech has come
back,'' Hayden said at an afternoon news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The 87-year-old former president also was likely recovered from
the small stroke he suffered during the Republican National
Convention, said Dr. Robert Schwartzman, chief of neurology at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had complained of a swollen tongue since before his trip to
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the swelling was the result of an exceedingly rare
bacterial infection known as actinomycosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so rare, we're calling it the president's syndrome,''
joked Calvin McDowell, a spokesman for the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will remain on antibiotics for at least six weeks, Hayden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford was strong, and although the one-hour
operation required general anesthesia, he was able to walk around
later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said Ford should be released later this week, but he
didn't want to set a specific date.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have said Ford wouldn't need rehabilitation therapy. He
had regained the use of his left hand and was sleeping well, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The former president has been eager to leave the hospital and
get on the campaign trail on behalf of GOP presidential nominee
George W. Bush and vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney, who was
Ford's White House chief of staff in 1975-76, McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's wife, Betty, and three of his four children visited with
him Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's in great spirits,'' McDowell said. ''Everyone is very
excited. Mrs. Ford is calling it a 'beautiful day and beautiful
news.'''
</P>
