<HEADLINE> Media Magnate Kidnapped in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By OLIVIER ACUNA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CULIACAN, Mexico (AP) -- A powerful media magnate was kidnapped
in Mexico's drug-plagued Sinaloa state, prompting police to lay low
and his family and newspapers to keep silent in a bid to protect
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Saturday that police checkpoints have been closed
down in the newspaper owner's hometown of Los Mochis out of fear
for the safety of Ildefonso Salido, 62.
</P>
<P>
   Salido, one of the richest men in the northern Mexican state,
was abducted Wednesday from a sports complex in the Pacific coast
city, about 130 miles north of the state capital of Culiacan.
Kidnappers are asking for $10 million for his release, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The region's main newspaper, El Debate, owned by Salido, has not
covered the kidnapping at the request of his family, a columnist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The family said in no way should authorities or the media
intervene,'' said Martin Mendoza, columnist for El Debate.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jose Ramos Santos, director of El Debate, said the
paper also had not filed a criminal complaint or asked police to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have not identified the four men who, posing as
federal police officers, abducted Salido as he exercised at a track
in Los Mochis.
</P>
<P>
   Police searched local hotels, but did not find the victim or the
suspects. Kidnappings and drug-related executions have been
frequent in the state in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Salido also owns two sister papers and has holdings in several
farming and farm-supply companies in Sinaloa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
