<HEADLINE> Suspect in hit-and-run death waives extradition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK MILLS, N.Y. (AP) - The main suspect in a fatal
hit-and-run accident pleaded innocent in village court Friday night
to charges of leaving the scene of a fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   Police this week transported 35-year-old Scott S. Zimmers from
his mother's home in Coweta County, Ga., about 40 miles south of
Atlanta. Investigators allege Zimmers fled there after the pickup
truck he was driving struck and killed 57-year-old Joan E. Foley as
she walked along a rural road south of Utica on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was walking home from the Oneida County Fire Convention.
Her body was found in a ditch Sunday morning by her husband.
Investigators believe Zimmers also attended the firemen's
convention and was on his way to a tavern in Waterville, 14 miles
south of Utica, when he struck the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmers drove south alone and apparently did not tell anyone
what police said was the true nature of his urgent trip. He
deceived family members as he tried to cover up his alleged
involvement, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmers explained the damage to his truck by saying he struck a
deer in Pennsylvania while driving to Georgia, deputies said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmers is currently being held without bail at Oneida County
Correctional Facility.
</P>
</TEXT>
