<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Visit Western Fires Area  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton will visit military
troops fighting forest fires in the West next week, the White House
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans a trip Tuesday to Boise, Idaho, where he will get
a briefing on the status of firefighting efforts, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said. Clinton also is slated to make a
second stop closer to the front lines of a fire in Idaho, where he
will meet some of the troops sent in to relieve exhausted civilian
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president wanted to just let the firefighters know how
much the country appreciates what they are doing,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the West on Saturday, about 70 large fires were burning
on more than 747,100 acres, according to the National Fire
Information Center. The biggest, in Idaho, had charred at least
102,000 acres near the Montana border.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart did not say whether Clinton plans to announce any new
grants or other assistance from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a short trip. Clinton is due back on the East Coast
for a Democratic fund-raiser Tuesday night at the home of
Charlottesville, Va., political patron Patricia Kluge. The event is
expected to bring in $500,000, much of which is intended to help
the presidential campaign of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, more than 62,000 wildfires, mostly in the
West, have burned 3.8 million acres. Assistant Interior Secretary
Sylvia Baca has called it the worst fire season in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Army soldiers and Marines have been sent to help
weary civilian fire crews, and Forest Service chief Mike Dombeck
announced Friday that 200 Canadian firefighters were coming to
Montana to help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
