<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast lawmakers explore ways to lower prescription drug prices  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL MELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) - Northeast states can band together to
force lower prescription drug prices without hurting manufacturers'
long-term profits, a Boston University professor said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the solution, legislation requiring drug makers to slash
prices to increase purchases by consumers, could take years to
implement, health services professor Alan Sager said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may take a few years but if we don't start now we won't get
there. There is no alternative,'' Sager said.
</P>
<P>
   Sager's report, ''Cutting Prescription Drug Spending By Paying
Federal Supply Schedule Prices,'' was the centerpiece of Saturday's
meeting of Northeast lawmakers seeking ways to curb prescription
drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturers this year will be paid $18 billion by private
insurers, government programs and residents of the eight states for
brand name prescription drugs, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Sager said the states can save a combined $6.5 billion in the
first year by forcing drug makers to offer them prescription drugs
at the same lower prices paid by the federal government, under the
Federal Supply Schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from New England, New York and Pennsylvania have been
meeting on an ad hoc basis for months. The group is organized as a
nonprofit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this association is trying to do is find a way to fair
prices while drug makers are trying to sustain unfair prices,''
Vermont state Sen. Peter Shumlin, D-Putney, said Saturday. ''This
is a war we have to win for our constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers at the meeting, however, said they preferred to
take a more conciliatory approach with drug makers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to look at the big picture of health care costs and
why they are so high,'' said state Sen. Timothy F. Murphy,
R-Harrisburg. ''We need to find a way to do this without getting
any specific group in the crosshairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would meet again in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not there yet, but there is agreement that it makes
sense for us to get together,'' Rhode Island Lt. Gov. Charles
Fogarty, a Democrat, said Friday. ''With states fighting separate
battles, it is easy for the opposition to overwhelm them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sager said drug manufacturers' apparent unwillingness to lower
prices means the states may have to act with legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Average drug prices in the United States are higher than
anywhere else, he said. Prices paid in seven wealthy nations to
drug makers in 1997-98 ranged between 14.5 percent less in
Switzerland to 38.5 percent less in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The report claims the eight U.S. states have a combined buying
power greater than Germany, where prices paid to drug makers in
1997-98 were 21 percent less than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the report estimates the eight states have 10 million
residents, or 23 percent of the total population, with no insurance
for prescription drugs. Seniors make up slightly more than
one-fifth, or 22 percent, of that group.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Massachusetts has an estimated 303,000 seniors
without coverage. But the state this year passed legislation
offering all people age 65 and older affordable prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Sager said winning significant concessions on prescription drug
prices will force drug makers' profits down initially. But the
report claims lower prices will increase demand and eventually help
manufacturers recoup losses.
</P>
<P>
   The report, produced at no cost to the association of lawmakers,
suggested the states could jointly negotiate fair profit margins
for drug manufacturers. The states could also help finance research
on new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Senate Ways and Means Chairman Mark Montigny,
D-New Bedford, said his state recently passed legislation allowing
it to negotiate bulk purchases of prescription drugs for various
government programs. He estimated it would result in 25 to 35
percent savings.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty said association members are also looking closely at
Maine's recent move to negotiate lower prescription prices on
behalf of more than 300,000 uncovered residents.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state law, if negotiations with manufacturers fail to
reduce prices significantly, the state could impose price controls
three years from now. A similar bill failed in Vermont this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sager said the Maine law shows states have the power to control
the rising cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is the world's shock absorber for drug
manufacturers,'' he said. ''There is no functioning market to fix
the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 1945 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000805.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> List Dwindles for U.S. Baseball  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The U.S. Olympic baseball team might have only
one retired major leaguer on the roster, leaving the rest of the
slots for minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines, playing in the independent Atlantic League, is a
strong candidate for the team, baseball steering committee
co-chairman Bob Watson said Saturday evening. Raines played most of
last season for Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the retired players under consideration have either
dropped out, gotten hurt or failed to impress. Terry Steinbach, who
had an inside track as a catcher, tore a hamstring and won't be
able to play next month in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was really on course to be one of our catchers,'' Watson
said, in a telephone interview. ''That would have been really great
because of his experience and ability to handle the pitching
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of other retired major leaguers were invited to play in
amateur, semipro or minor leagues to get back into shape and try
out for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Raines was the only one still in the running for the team
Saturday. Countries must have their rosters set by Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just about everybody else has fallen by the wayside,'' Watson
said. ''It was wishful thinking that guys could have taken some
months off, mentally shut it down and then ask them to come back
and start playing again to be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Actually, Pat Kelly made a strong showing but second base is
one of the positions we're pretty deep in.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection committee is working with major league teams to
try to get some of their best Triple-A and Double-A players. This
is the first Olympic baseball tournament that will be open to
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba won the tournaments in Barcelona and Atlanta, the first two
in which medals were awarded. Introducing professionals is expected
to narrow the gap between Cuba and the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Japan expects to have eight players from its major league teams,
including Seibu Lions pitcher Daisuke Matsuzaka. Several Japanese
teams were reluctant to let players go for the Olympics, preferring
to keep them for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The United States ran into the same problem last year in
choosing players for the Pan Am team that qualified for the Olympic
tournament. Watson said teams have been reluctant again this year
to part with top prospects during September.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teams are in the pennant race,'' Watson said. ''Pitchers,
center fielders, catchers, shortstops -- those guys are hard to come
by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
