<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescription Drug Prices Discussed  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL MELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Northeast lawmakers seeking ways to curb
prescription drug prices discussed banding together to force
manufacturers to lower prices Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the discussion was a Boston University
professor's report suggesting that legislation requiring drug
makers to slash prices would result in increased purchases by
consumers and therefore not cut into the drug manufacturers'
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may take a few years but if we don't start now we won't get
there. There is no alternative,'' health services professor Alan
Sager, the report's author, told the group.
</P>
<P>
   This year, drug manufacturers will be paid $18 billion for brand
name prescription drugs by private insurers, government programs
and residents of the eight Northeast states, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A combined $6.5 billion could be saved in the first year by
forcing drug makers to offer prescription drugs at the same lower
prices paid by the federal government, under the Federal Supply
Schedule, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers from New England, New York and Pennsylvania have
been meeting on an ad hoc basis for months.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this association is trying to do is find a way to fair
prices while drug makers are trying to sustain unfair prices,''
Vermont Sen. Peter Shumlin, a Democrat, said Saturday. ''This is a
war we have to win for our constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers at the meeting took a more conciliatory
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to look at the big picture of health care costs and
why they are so high,'' said Pennsylvania Sen. Timothy F. Murphy, a
Republican. ''We need to find a way to do this without getting any
specific group in the cross hairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The group plans to meet again in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not there yet, but there is agreement that it makes
sense for us to get together,'' Rhode Island's Democratic Lt. Gov.
Charles Fogarty said on Friday. ''With states fighting separate
battles, it is easy for the opposition to overwhelm them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, 23 percent of the Northeast states'
population had no insurance for prescription drugs, with seniors
making up about one-fifth of that group.
</P>
<P>
   The report, produced at no cost to the association of lawmakers,
suggested the states could jointly negotiate fair profit margins
for drug manufacturers and help finance research on new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Sen. Mark Montigny, a Democrat, said his state
recently passed legislation allowing it to negotiate bulk purchases
of prescription drugs for various government programs, something he
estimated would result in 25 to 35 percent savings.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty said association members also were looking at Maine's
recent move to negotiate lower prescription prices on behalf of
more than 300,000 uncovered residents. Under the state law, if
negotiations with manufacturers fail to reduce prices
significantly, the state could impose price controls three years
from now. A similar bill failed in Vermont this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is the world's shock absorber for drug
manufacturers,'' Sager said. ''There is no functioning market to
fix the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Health Care Association: http://www.ahca.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 1957 </TRAILER>
