<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soldiers Find Fireline Life Hard  </HEADLINE>
By KELLY TEAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURGDORF, Idaho (AP) -- Sgt. Brad Rhoden traded his M-16 for a
pick and shovel and dug in against a wildfire in the Idaho
mountains, breathing smoke and ash in thin mountain air, sweating
in triple-digit temperatures and trudging up and down rugged
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hiking is worse than in Bosnia, and the living conditions
are better there,'' Rhoden said as he and nearly 600 others from
Fort Hood, Texas, became the first Army soldiers to begin battling
blazes that have stretched resources thin across the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has nothing to do with what I trained for,'' Rhoden said.
''I'm here because my country needs me.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 62,000 wildfires have charred 3.8 million acres so far
this year in what officials are calling the worst Western fire
season in 50 years. Firefighters from states as far away as
Delaware continued to battle 70 large fires active across the West
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Army soldiers, 500 Marines had joined
firefighters in Idaho and a second battalion of Marines arrived in
Idaho on Saturday from Camp Pendleton, Calif. The Forest Service
also announced Friday that 200 additional Canadian firefighters and
500 additional U.S. Army troops were joining the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Saturday that President Clinton would
visit military troops fighting wildfires in Idaho on Tuesday. ''The
president wanted to just let the firefighters know how much the
country appreciates what they are doing,'' White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoden and his fellow soldiers were given two days of training
last week, shown how to cut fire lines, dig ditches and create
escape routes, then they were sent Friday to battle a 20,000-acre
fire 25 miles north of McCall in the Payette National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The fire is far from the biggest in the West -- an Idaho blaze
near the Montana state line has blackened 102,000 acres -- but the
soldiers' presence is allowing experienced Forest Service crews to
tackle other assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Military forces have been sent in as reinforcements to help the
nation's 20,000 civilian wildfire fighters previously, most
recently in 1996. The worst year was 1988, when eight battalions,
57 helicopters and eight air tankers helped battle flames that
ravaged Yellowstone National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoden and several friends talked about their new combat duty
while taking refuge from the hot sun in a relatively spacious mess
tent.
</P>
<P>
   In Idaho for less than a week, their eyes were bloodshot, feet
blistered and grimy uniforms smelled of smoke. When they have had
time for breaks, they've slept in canvas pup tents pitched on
steep, rocky ground. There are only eight showers for the entire
battalion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kuwait wasn't hard compared to this place,'' Staff Sgt. Ian
Campbell said with a wry smile. ''Here you're constantly working.
It's something I haven't seen in a while: Soldiers getting in the
dirt and just working.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers had been trudging through thick ash, putting out
embers inside a secured fire line that has been protecting a
settlement of several dozen homes.
</P>
<P>
   Their weapons: 10-pound pulaskis, a combination adz and ax, and
McLeods, a combination shovel and pick that weigh about the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather have my M-16,'' Rhoden said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Sylvester Gary had been assigned to fires before and knew
some of what to expect. But struggling up and down an Idaho
mountain was taking a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ''That bad boy was hard on my feet,'' Gary said. ''I thought I
was in shape before I came here.''
</P>
<P>
   But morale is high.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're saving peoples' lives, we're helping safeguard this
property out here,'' said Lt. Col. Darryl Williams, who commands
the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said firefighting gives the soldiers ''a great
opportunity to showcase what the military does best. We're able to
react to a situation very quickly, and we're doing pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't diminish their respect for the civilians who
normally hold this duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Firefighters are the true American heroes,'' Rhoden said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Fire Information Center: http://www.nifc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 2034 </TRAILER>
