<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. City Settles Federal Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMTRAMCK, Mich. (AP) -- The city was ordered to revamp local
voting procedures in settling a federal lawsuit that accused local
poll workers of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Some Arab-Americans in Hamtramck had complained following last
November's election that poll workers questioned their citizenship
based on physical appearance and English language skills.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent federal investigation found that Arab-Americans and
''other dark-skinned voters'' were required to take a citizenship
oath prior to being permitted to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached Friday calls on Hamtramck to ''revamp its
election procedures to ensure that all voters are treated
equally,'' the U.S. Justice Department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the agreement requires a training program for
election officials; removal of discriminating poll workers;
bilingual election workers; notices of the new practices in several
languages; and federal monitoring of Hamtramck elections.
</P>
<P>
   Hamtramck is a city of about 20,000 near Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
