<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Civil Rights Pioneer Honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Va. (AP) -- A black woman who refused to give up her
bus seat to white passengers in 1944 was honored Saturday as a
civil rights pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Morgan, 83, was arrested for that action in eastern
Virginia more than a decade before Rosa Parks gained recognition
for also refusing to give up her seat on a bus in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's case, appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court by then-NAACP
lawyer Thurgood Marshall, resulted in the court striking down
segregation in interstate transportation. Marshall later became the
high court's first black justice.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 people packed Gloucester County's historic Colonial
Courthouse on Saturday to honor Morgan. The ceremony is an early
part of the county's 350th anniversary celebration, which will be
held next year.
</P>
<P>
   She dabbed her cheek with a handkerchief when a soloist sang,
''Oh Freedom ... Before I'll be your slave, I'll be buried in my
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, she told reporters, ''We still have a long
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In was a muggy July morning when Morgan, then a young mother,
boarded a Greyhound bus in Hayes Store, took a seat in the back and
headed for home in Baltimore. She was recovering from surgery and
had brought her two children to stay temporarily with her mother in
Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles down the road, the bus driver told Morgan to move
because a white couple wanted to occupy her row.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'Well, no,''' recalled Morgan, who now lives on New
York's Long Island. ''That was a seat I had paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was illegal in Virginia and nine other states
for blacks to sit next to whites on buses. Morgan was jailed for
refusing to move and for resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said she willingly paid a $100 fine for resisting arrest
because she did kick the Middlesex County sheriff who tried to
remove her from the bus and she did scratch the deputy who took her
to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother posted her $500 bail, but Morgan wouldn't pay a $10
fine and $5.25 in court costs for refusing to give up her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked where her courage that day came from, Morgan said simply,
''I can't understand how anyone would have done otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers Saturday praised Morgan's efforts for fighting
racism.
</P>
<P>
   ''She took a stand not to stand,'' said Dorothy Cooke,
chairperson of the Multicultural Committee for the 350th
celebration. ''As a result of that,'' Cooke said, ''our lives have
never been the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000805.0113 </DOCNO>
