<HEADLINE> Water-use fight between airport business, town goes to court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW WINDSOR, N.Y. (AP) - A lawsuit filed by Rifton Aviation
Services would force the town of New Windsor to open the spigot to
their new multimillion-dollar corporate jet hangar at Stewart
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The town locked the valve Thursday, saying Rifton sucked more
than 100,000 gallons of town water into its firefighting pipeline
without permission, leaving leaving several airport hydrants as
well as the airport administration building dry.
</P>
<P>
   Rifton president Christian Domer is going to state Supreme Court
Monday to get a judge to impose an injunction against New Windsor
and state officials so Rifton can get its water flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're entitled to the water. It's in our lease with the
state,'' Rifton lawyer Gerald Jacobowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   New Windsor Town Supervisor George Meyers says the water was not
paid for because Rifton has never been able to get its water-use
permit approved and doesn't have a meter on its line.
</P>
<P>
   New Windsor is 47 miles north of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
