<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers 13, Dolphins 10  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Chris Fuamatu-Ma'afala, seemingly the
forgotten man in Pittsburgh's backfield, scored the Steelers' only
touchdown and set up Kris Brown's winning field goal with a 50-yard
run in a 13-10 comeback preseason victory over the Miami Dolphins
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins ushered in the post-Dan Marino era by going without
a touchdown until the third quarter, an inept performance offset by
an even more dismal showing by a still-struggling Steelers offense
that finished with minus-5 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   Fuamatu-Ma'afala provided about the only offensive excitement,
scoring the tying touchdown on a 3-yard run with 6:41 left, then
running 50 yards to the 15 before Brown's 21-yard game-winner with
1:34 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Druckenmiller, projected as Miami's third-team quarterback,
did what starter Damon Huard couldn't, by leading a 78-yard drive
for the game's first touchdown and a 10-3 Dolphins lead at 4:07 of
the third.
</P>
<P>
   Autry Denson broke three tackles on a 26-yard gain on a
third-and-13 swing pass to the Steelers' 23, and Denson later
scored from the 2 for the Dolphins' only lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers' offense, ineffective behind Kordell Stewart and
backup Kent Graham, finally started moving when rookie Tee Martin
of Tennessee took over and began handing off to Fuamatu-Ma'afala.
He gained 122 yards on 15 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Fuamatu-Ma'afala usually is the backup fullback, but played
mostly at running back with Jerome Bettis out with a knee injury
and Richard Huntley playing only a few plays because of an injured
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Both offenses looked overmatched against the opposing starting
defenses in a first half in which they combined for only 66 passing
yards -- only 2 by the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, clearly an altered offense with Dan Marino retired
and former Cowboys coach Chan Gailey now calling the plays,
emphasized running plays and swing passes without much success.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, who apparently won the Dolphins' quarterback derby by
default when Jay Fiedler underwent hip surgery last week, had an
underwhelming debut as Marino's replacement. He was 8-of-14 for 64
yards, rarely testing the Steelers' defense with anything except
short, timing passes.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, coming off two consecutive poor seasons that have
jeopardized his future with the Steelers, was even worse. Rarely
getting time to throw by a blitzing Dolphins defense, he looked
confused and hesitant to throw, going 0-for-6 while generating
offense only by scrambling twice for 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, booed frequently last season as the Steelers were swept
at home by their AFC Central rivals, wasn't even out of the first
quarter before hearing his first sustained booing.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, the slow-afoot Kent Graham, wasn't much better
even against Dolphins defensive backups, finishing 2-for-5 for 19
yards while being sacked four times for 23 yards in losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers' only first-half scoring was set up by a 30-yard
pass interference call on Ray Hill that set up Kris Brown's 30-yard
field goal with 11:30 left in the second quarter. Later, a 31-yard
interference call on Orlando Steinauer led to Fuamatu-Ma'afala's
tying score.
</P>
<P>
   It was a significant contrast to last Sunday, when the Steelers
-- aided by four Dallas turnovers -- scored 38 points in the first
half of a 38-10 victory over the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, looking like a team playing its preseason opener,
tied it at 3 on Olindo Mare's 33-yard field goal at 3:40 following
Leslie Shepherd's 46-yard punt return.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller went 13-of-21 for 141 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 2120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000805.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rosenfeld Wins US Junior Amateur  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH PLAINS, Ore. (AP) -- Matthew Rosenfeld led from start to
finish Saturday, and beat Ryan Moore 3 and 2 to win the US Junior
Amateur Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Ferrero won the girls title, scoring a 3 and 1 victory over
Ina Kim on the par-72 Witch Hollow Course at Pumpkin Ridge Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld, of Plano, Texas, never trailed, but was pushed most
of the way by Moore, a big hitter from Puyallup, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the first hole, Moore hit a 260-yard 3-wood to
within six feet on the par-5 fourth hole. He then made his putt for
an eagle to even the match.
</P>
<P>
   Moore couldn't hold the momentum, though, as errant tee shots
cost him on the next two holes. Moore came back for a birdie on the
next hole (No. 7) to close Rosenfeld's lead to one, but that would
be as close as Moore would come.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld pushed his lead back to 2-up when he sank a difficult
6-foot birdie putt on the 562-yard par-5 eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ''It felt like it was 30 feet,'' Rosenfeld said of his clutch
putt. ''I think 8 was the turning point for the match.''
</P>
<P>
   After halving the next four holes, Rosenfeld took his biggest
lead of the day, at 3-up, when he parred and Moore bogeyed No. 13,
a 381-yard par 4.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld immediately gave that hole back, however, when he
lipped out a short par putt on par 3 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought the momentum changed a little bit there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore wasn't so sure, though.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew it wouldn't affect him much because he's such a great
player,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld birdied the next hole, the par 5 15th, then halved No.
16 to end the match.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time since 1992 that the medalist from the
preliminary rounds went on to win the championship. Rosenfeld also
became the first player to make it to the semifinals in
back-to-back years since Tiger Woods did it in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld lost last year to Hunter Mahan, who was ineligible to
play in this year's junior tournament after turning 18.
</P>
<P>
   In the girls' event, Ferrero, of Lodi, Calif., got off to a
great start by winning five of the first six holes. After giving
one back, Ferrero pushed her advantage to 6-up with a par 3 on No.
11.
</P>
<P>
   ''At that point, I knew all I had to do was tie two holes and
win one and I would win the match,'' Ferrero said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that pressure didn't bother Kim, of Encino, Calif.,
who won four of the next five holes with birdies and cut Ferrero's
lead to 2-up with two holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero ended the comeback with a birdie on the par 4 17th.
</P>
<P>
   She automatically qualified for this week's US Women's Amateur
with the win. Ferrero decided against playing at the tournament, to
be held at Portland's Waverly Country Club. Instead, she will play
in an amateur tournament in the midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
