<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAfranio Coutinho:
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Afranio Coutinho, a member of the
Brazilian Academy of Letters and a promoter of Brazilian literature
overseas, died Saturday. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Coutinho was named to the prestigious Brazilian Academy of
Letters in 1962 after teaching the country's literature to
generations of students here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   His 1955 study ''Literature in Brazil'' has been translated into
several languages, the academy said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Coutinho was a visiting professor of Brazilian
Literature at Columbia University in New York, where he also
studied in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, he amassed a personal library that served as the
foundation for the Afranio Coutinho Literary Office in Rio, a
research center and library for international and Brazilian
scholars.
Mustafa Mitwali:
</P>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Mustafa Mitwali, a popular Egyptian film and
stage actor, died Saturday of a heart attack. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Mitwali starred in several plays with Egypt's popular comedian
Adel Imam, including ''A Witness Who Saw Nothing,'' ''Seyed, the
Servant,'' ''The Leader'' and ''Bodyguard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitwali started his career in television soap operas and acted
in historical dramas for many years. His first film was ''Bab
Zuweila,'' directed by Nour el-Damerdash.
Helen Quinn:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Helen Quinn, self-appointed manager of the
Metropolitan Opera's standing-room tickets line for 32 years, died
Wednesday of food poisoning. She was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday morning, Quinn arrived at the opera house with a
bullhorn and a clipboard. She took charge of the willing crowd of
opera buffs who came to buy that week's allotment of standing-room
tickets, and were then free to trickle off to do anything but wait
in line.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn had been doing this without pay every Saturday since 1968
when she decided one day while standing in line at the Met to put
an end to the bickering.
</P>
<P>
   She saw her first opera, Mozart's ''The Magic Flute,'' while
still in high school in 1943, and became such a fan that she
eventually moved to an apartment on West 57th Street near the Met.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
