<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. packing firm making second recall of suspect beef  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - A Pennsylvania meat processor is recalling
more than a quarter-million pounds of beef that may be contaminated
with potentially deadly E. coli bacteria, a week after it withdrew
346,700 pounds of suspect ground beef, the Agriculture Department
said Saturday. Some of the meat was shipped to wholesalers in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The latest recall involves 253,350 pounds of MOPAC brand pure
ground beef, pure ground sirloin, pure ground round and pure ground
chuck, produced by Moyer Packing Co., of Souderton, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The products were produced on July 19 in 10-pound packages that
bear the establishment number 1311 and the date 07/19/00. They were
shipped in boxes weighing 40 to 60 pounds to wholesalers in New
Jersey, New York, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland, Virginia,
West Virginia, Rhode Island, Pennsylvania and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The products may have been reground and repackaged at the retail
level, USDA said, and consumers may wish to check with their
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   No illnesses have been reported from this batch, whose recall
was triggered when a sample of reground beef collected July 26 from
a retail store tested positive for E. coli O157:H7, USDA said.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli bacteria can cause bloody diarrhea and dehydration.
People who are very young, the elderly and those with weakened
immune systems are most in danger of fatal complications.
</P>
<P>
   The first recall, announced July 29, involved 346,700 pounds of
ground beef, distributed at the wholesale level in 5- and 10-pound
packages. They also were suspected of possible E. coli
contamination, but no illnesses were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
