<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Power Grid Strained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Three power plants failed late last week
during California's extended heat wave, sapping the state's power
reserves and prompting officials to declare a low-level emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The plant failures -- one in Northern California on Thursday and
two in Southern California on Friday -- weren't noticed by consumers
because other plants took up the slack, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the outages pushed the state's power reserves below 7
percent, forcing the agency that manages the power grid to impose a
stage-one emergency Friday. Stage one is the lowest level of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, California Independent System Operator
declared stage-two alerts, which result in voluntary reductions by
large electricity customers. A stage-two alert occurs when reserves
fall below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   California has never had a stage-three emergency, declared when
reserves fall below 1.5 percent, but it came perilously close
Tuesday and Wednesday, as heavy demand strained resources across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Power plants went without routine maintenance under a five-day,
''no-touch'' directive. The order, which has been issued at least
17 times this year, prohibits all but emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the outages are indicative of a system which has
been pushed to capacity for a long time, by hot weather, a growing
population and heavy demand from industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''This very much demonstrates the fact that we have been running
this system hard for more than two months,'' agency spokesman
Patrick Dorinson said. ''That's taken a toll, not only on the power
plants, but also on the operators and everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   California Energy Commission: www.energy.ca.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
