<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lehman Withdraws From International  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTLE ROCK, Colo. (AP) -- Tied for fourth place at the halfway
point and visibly limping on an injured right knee, Tom Lehman
withdrew from The International on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He was scheduled to undergo an MRI for a possible torn
cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, seventh on the PGA Tour money list this season, limped
noticeably while walking down the fairway from the No. 10 tee box
on Friday. Moments earlier, he had hit an awkward shot from behind
the ninth green that cost him a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was unable to finish his second round because of a
lightning delay late Friday. He played the final two holes of his
second round Saturday morning, then withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was OK for the first 20 or 22 holes, then I felt it and
struggled the rest of the way,'' Lehman said. ''My knee started to
swell, and after my round this morning I had it drained. It swelled
back up, however, and I just do not feel I need to take any chances
on these hills.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I'm disappointed because I was playing really well
for those first 20 or so holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, the first-round co-leader with 15 points, had 23 points
after two rounds. He trailed second-round leader Ernie Els by 11
points under the modified Stableford scoring system used in this
event.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LEFTY IS LURKING: Phil Mickelson, the International's only
two-time champion, stands eight points out of the lead entering the
final round -- a margin he admits is formidable but not
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, being way back, I understand it is going to be
difficult and it is unlikely,'' Mickelson said of Ernie Els' lead.
''But tomorrow I feel like if I get hot, make some birdies and
possibly an eagle or two, I may be able to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows if he goes out and plays solid golf, makes the
birdies on the par-5s, an odd birdie here or there, he is going to
be almost uncatchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson likes the fact he has been able to shoot at every pin
on the course because of the soft greens.
</P>
<P>
   ''There really hasn't been one pin that I have not tried to go
after,'' he said. ''So it won't alter the way I'm playing. I just
need to get hot with the putter and give myself a lot of
opportunities. I'm going to be ultra-aggressive trying to make
eagles. The format allows you to make up ground quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson made a miracle birdie on the 13th hole Saturday after
driving behind trees and pitching out short of the green. He
chipped in, moving to 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared to have driven into a creek on the 17th hole
but got a break.
</P>
<P>
   ''The marshal told me my ball hit a rock in the stream and just
skipped it right across,'' he said. ''I was able to advance it by
the green and get up and down (for birdie). I was very fortunate
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SERGIO SURGES: Sergio Garcia, the 20-year-old Spaniard who has
had an up-and-down season, moved up the leaderboard with a
nine-point round for a total of 30.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still there,'' Garcia said. ''We need a really good run
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia scrambled to make a birdie after someone apparently
stepped on his ball just off the 18th fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure somebody did, but nobody wanted to admit it,'' Garcia
said. ''If you throw 20 balls, you're not going to get a lie like
that. The grass is lined toward the fairway. I don't know how a
ball coming across the grass can be lying so down, and there was a
little mark on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ''My dad (Victor) was there and he said the ball wasn't lying
like that, but the referees didn't believe my dad. My dad is a
professional golfer. He's never cheated, and I don't think he's
going to cheat for me.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I was able to get over that and hit a great shot and make
a beautiful putt. I hit a hard 7-iron, 179 yards into the wind. It
was a hell of a shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
