<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Aug. 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton To Visit Western Fires Area
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton will visit military troops
fighting forest fires in the West next week, the White House said today. Clinton
plans a trip Tuesday to Boise, Idaho, where he will get a briefing on the status
of firefighting efforts, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. Clinton also
is slated to make a second stop closer to the front lines of a fire in Idaho,
where he will meet some of the troops sent in to relieve exhausted civilian
firefighters. Across the West, about 70 large fires were burning today on more
than 747,100 acres, according to the National Fire Information Center.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Attacks Gore for Clinton Veto
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SCHOOLCRAFT, Mich. (AP) -- George W. Bush, campaigning by train across an
important midwestern battleground state, today sought to portray rival Al Gore
as both anti-family and timid. The GOP nominee seized on President Clinton's
announcement earlier in the day that he would veto legislation to repeal the
so-called marriage penalty in the tax code. ''Al Gore had a chance to stand up
to President Clinton and say don't veto that bill. But he was silent. He had
nothing to say,'' Bush told a railside rally in East Lansing. Gore dismissed
Bush's accusations, saying the congressional proposal would only have benefitted
the wealthy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pa. Meat Processor Recalls Beef
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Pennsylvania meat processor is recalling more than a
quarter-million pounds of beef that may be contaminated with potentially deadly
E. coli bacteria, a week after it withdraw 346,700 pounds of suspect ground
beef, the Agriculture Department said today. The latest recall involves 253,350
pounds of MOPAC brand pure ground beef, pure ground sirloin, pure ground round
and pure ground chuck, produced by Moyer Packing Co. of Souderton, Pa.. The
products were produced on July 19 and were shipped to wholesalers in New York,
New Jersey, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland, Virginia, West Virginia, Rhode
Island, Pennsylvania and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Calif. Power Grid Strained
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Continued high temperatures pushed the state's power grid
nearly to its limits as three power plants failed last week. Other power plants
were able to take up the slack after an outage Thursday in Northern California
and two outages yesterday in Southern California. But the state's power reserves
fell below 7 percent, and the agency that manages the power grid imposed a
stage-one emergency, the lowest level emergency, yesterday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NAACP Moves Convention Out of S.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The NAACP is moving its annual state convention out of
South Carolina to protest the state's decision to continue to fly the
Confederate battle flag on Statehouse grounds. James Gallman, president of the
NAACP's South Carolina conference of branches, said the decision by lawmakers to
move the flag to a Confederate Soldier Monument after bringing it down from the
Capitol dome was insulting.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
India Blames Pakistan for Killings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Calling for a major overhaul of India's internal
anti-terrorism system, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee blamed Pakistan on
Saturday for a series of attacks that killed 102 people in Kashmir. Vajpayee
accused India's neighbor of everything from indulging in carnage like the
Kashmir killings earlier this week and planning bomb attacks on Christian
churches to ordering the circulation of fake currency notes and aiding a
festering insurgency in the remote northeastern states.
</P>
