<HEADLINE> President Visits Kennedy Compound  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS PORT, Mass. (AP) -- Two days after George W. Bush accused
him of a failure of leadership, President Clinton said Saturday
night that Republicans had run America into a ditch in 1992 and ''I
have done everything I could to turn the country around.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''Do not blow this election. The best is still out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that helped raise more than $800,000 for Maryland
Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, one of the Kennedy family's
rising political stars, Clinton also said that if Bush's
tax-reduction program succeeds there will be no money left for the
rest of the country's needs, including defense and fixing Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   He told his audience that the help of all Democrats is needed to
deny Republicans an election victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that you do your job now and that we not sit on
our laurels won over the last eight years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I listened to a lot of those guys at the (Republican)
convention,'' he said. ''It sounded to me like they thought I had
interrupted the ordinary flow of things when I got elected.
</P>
<P>
   ''You didnt have to be a genius in 1992 to know that the country
was in a real ditch and if you were going to get out of it it was
going to take some real thought,'' he said. ''I have done
everything I could in seven and a half years to turn the country
around.''
</P>
<P>
   And without referring to Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney
by name, he said, ''No one is entitled to any of these jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe that anybody is entitled to serve but I
believe that before any one serves people have to believe they know
what they are doing,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   On his first visit to the storied vacation compound, Clinton
took a tour courtesy of Townsend, a daughter of the late Robert F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop was the shingled house used by John F. Kennedy
during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to seek the Democratic nomination for governor in 2002,
Townsend is a leader in the centrist Democratic Leadership
Conference, a group close to Clinton's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing Clinton, Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., said he should
be considered for the Nobel peace prize for his efforts at Camp
David to broker peace in the Middle East. And referring to the last
eight years of economic growth, Kennedy said, ''Thank You Mr.
Strong Economy President.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests were paying $2,000 to $4,000 to attend the party, the
most lucrative of four scheduled this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The other three events were to benefit Hillary Clinton's Senate
campaign in New York and were expected to raise an estimated
$525,000.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of golf on Martha's Vineyard, the Clinton
family's favorite vacation spot, Clinton bought a double-dip
raspberry and peaches-and-cream cone at Mad Martha's ice cream
store in Vineyard Haven, then stuffed some cash into the tip jar
and walked outside. There he handed what was left of his cone to
his Labrador retriever, Buddy, and said as the dog wolfed it down
in one gulp: ''Gotta share.''
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon round of golf behind him, Clinton and daughter
Chelsea, stopped the presidential motorcade at a bookstore in the
town of Vineyard Haven. Clinton bought three books, including, at
his daughter's suggestion, ''From Dawn to Decadence,'' French-born
historian Jacques Barzun's masterpiece about what he considers the
decline of Western culture since the Renaissance and Reformation
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-05-00 2207 </TRAILER>
