<HEADLINE> Cyclist hit by truck during 200-mile bike trek for charity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLEBOROUGH, Mass. (AP) - A cyclist from New Jersey riding in
a 200-mile bicycle ride for charity died Saturday after being hit
by an 18-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Heller, 61, of Roseland, N.J., was one of 3,000 cyclists
participating in the Pan-Massachusetts Challenge Ride, which raises
money for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Heller was hit on Route 28 after he got lost and rode off the
designated route for the race, according to a statement from Bill
Starr, founder and executive director of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone who rides is part of the PMC family,'' Starr said.
''This is a very sad day for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in the event's 21-year history that a
rider has been killed. A cyclist died in 1984 after running into a
van, said Mary Crotty, a spokeswoman for PMC.
</P>
