<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-05 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions, Verizon continue contract talks  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Hours ahead of a midnight strike deadline, a
union negotiator said Saturday that 87,200 telephone workers in 12
states from Maine to Virginia likely would walk off the job early
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A strike would delay repairs, new service orders, directory
assistance and billing inquiries for 25 million customers of
Verizon Communications, the nation's largest local and wireless
telephone company that was formed in June by the merger of Bell
Atlantic and GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It would not disrupt regular telephone service, 911 emergency
service or Verizon's fast-growing wireless operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America, which represents about
72,500 Verizon workers, and the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, which represents 14,700 more, have authorized a
strike at 12:01 a.m. EDT Sunday, when the unions' contract with
Verizon expires.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, it looks like there is no chance of a settlement by
midnight tonight,'' union negotiator Vince Maisano told about 50
workers at a mid-afternoon rally outside the hotel where contract
talks were taking place. ''The company is not really serious about
its employees, who have built this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations continued late into the night with one company
official expressing hope they would go past midnight if necessary
to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are here, we are talking, we are hoping the union will
continue to talk even after the strike deadline - through the night
and into tomorrow, as long as it takes,'' said Verizon spokesman
Eric Rabe.
</P>
<P>
   But told reporters Verizon managers would ''work very long
hours, seven days a week'' taking over customer service jobs if a
strike did occur.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll do whatever we have to do to provide service in the face
of the strike,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said the company was not considering hiring nonunion
workers to fill strikers' slots, but added that ''anything's
possible'' were a strike to continue for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon says its needs flexibility deciding what it pays
wireless workers in the rapidly emerging field. Verizon on Friday
submitted a proposed five-year contract that included a 3.5 percent
annual raise and various workplace concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the proposed contract did not cover the unions'
request for an easier way to unionize wireless workers because
Verizon owns only 55 percent of the wireless operation, which is a
separate company run through a joint venture with Vodafone
AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials want assurances the company will let union
workers take jobs in the expanding wireless operation and will give
the unions more opportunity to organize the 32,000 current wireless
workers, virtually all of whom are nonunion.
</P>
<P>
   Along with higher wages and concessions on working conditions
and job security, the unions also want Verizon to stop contracting
work in other rapidly growing areas, such as installation of
Internet service lines, to nonunion companies.
</P>
<P>
   Maisano said the major stumbling block was Verizon's refusal to
allow union workers to take jobs in the wireless operation and to
end contracts with nonunionized companies.
</P>
<P>
   Union members in the company's conventional telephone operation
lose union benefits if they take jobs in Verizon's wireless
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The unions want Verizon to allow organization of wireless
workers through a ''card check,'' an informal process labor leaders
say is less cumbersome than representation elections, which can
take months.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the company must also raise union wages and
improve job security and stop forcing employees to work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The states involved are Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, New York, New Jersey, Delaware,
Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia and West Virginia, along with the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com/home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-05-00 2225 </TRAILER>
