<HEADLINE> Wash. Sheriff's Deputy Fatally Shot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) -- A sheriff's deputy responding to a
domestic violence call and possible hostage situation was fatally
shot Saturday on the porch of a home, a sheriff's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators were trying to talk the alleged shooter, a man in
his 50s, into surrendering late Saturday. He was still in the home
and it wasn't clear whether he had any hostages, sheriff's
spokesman Jim Borte said.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Davis, 48, a deputy with the Clallam County Sheriff's
Department, was found shot in the head outside the house just
outside this coastal city on the Olympic Peninsula, about 60 miles
northwest of Seattle. He had responded to a domestic violence call
from a neighbor, Borte said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they had heard other muffled sounds that could have
been gunshots but could not immediately confirm whether more shots
were fired.
</P>
