<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, Aug. 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Vetoes GOP Marriage Tax Cut
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton vetoed a Republican-sponsored tax
cut for married couples today, describing it as ''the first installment of a
fiscally reckless tax strategy'' that would erase projected budget surpluses. He
said the tax break package amounted to little more than a gift to the wealthy.
The legislation passed both the House and the Senate by less than the two-thirds
majorities needed to override Clinton's veto, but a House leader said an
override attempt will be a top priority after Congress' current summer recess.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Recalls Atomic Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HIROSHIMA, Japan (AP) -- In a solemn annual rite, Japan paused Sunday to
recall the day 55 years ago when the dropping of a U.S. atomic bomb ''created a
hell on earth.'' Broken only by the steady chirping of cicadas and the tolling
of a bell, 60 seconds of silent prayer commenced at 8:15 a.m. -- the exact
moment the bomb exploded above Hiroshima on Aug. 6, 1945. Many in attendance on
the grounds of Peace Memorial Park bowed their heads, while some held Buddhist
prayer beads. The city of Hiroshima estimated that 50,000 people attended the
event, but police put the number at 30,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Tour To Lead to Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WESTHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Gore will sweep into the Democratic National
Convention fresh from a tour designed to demonstrate he will ''go the distance''
on the environment, welfare reform, tax relief, health care and other issues,
his campaign said today. The vice president and former senator of Tennessee will
travel from his hometown of Carthage through southern and Midwest states, with a
''handing of the baton'' to Gore from President Clinton in Michigan on Aug. 15,
spokesman Chris Lehane said. He then heads to the convention, Aug. 14 through
Aug. 17 in Los Angeles, to accept the presidential nomination.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton To Visit Western Fires Area
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton will visit military troops
fighting forest fires in the West next week, the White House said today. Clinton
plans a trip Tuesday to Boise, Idaho, where he will get a briefing on the status
of firefighting efforts, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. Clinton also
is slated to make a second stop closer to the front lines of a fire in Idaho,
where he will meet some of the troops sent in to relieve exhausted civilian
firefighters. Across the West, about 70 large fires were burning today on more
than 747,100 acres, according to the National Fire Information Center.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Presidential Traits Examined
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George and Al take note: A team of psychologists has
determined that great presidents tend to be take-charge guys. They are smart,
energetic and assertive, but not necessarily likable or straightforward.
''Agreeableness is highly desirable in a neighbor or spouse,'' the researchers
concluded. But when it comes to ranking the great national leaders,
''disagreeable presidents do somewhat better.'' Steven J. Rubenzer described the
research, which he conducted with Thomas J. Faschingbauer of Richmond, Texas and
Deniz S. Ones of the University of Minnesota. The three consulted with 115
presidential historians who helped rate the nation's 41 presidents on a complex,
600-question psychological scale.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
India Blames Pakistan for Killings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Calling for a major overhaul of India's internal
anti-terrorism system, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee blamed Pakistan on
Saturday for a series of attacks that killed 102 people in Kashmir. Vajpayee
accused India's neighbor of everything from indulging in carnage like the
Kashmir killings earlier this week and planning bomb attacks on Christian
churches to ordering the circulation of fake currency notes and aiding a
festering insurgency in the remote northeastern states.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Va. Civil Rights Pioneer Honored
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Va. (AP) -- A black woman who refused to give up her bus seat to
white passengers in 1944 was honored today as a civil rights pioneer. Irene
Morgan, 83, was arrested for that action in eastern Virginia more than a decade
before Rosa Parks gained recognition for also refusing to give up her seat on a
bus in Alabama. Morgan's case, appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court by then-NAACP
lawyer Thurgood Marshall, resulted in the court striking down segregation in
interstate transportation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mariners Defeat Yankees 6-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- David Cone, back from a 1&AMP;frac12;-week stay at New York's
minor league complex, struggled through six laborious innings today and remained
winless since April 28, as the Yankees fell to the Seattle Mariners 6-5. Cone,
37, once again tinkered with his mechanics -- throwing more over the top this
time -- but the results weren't much better. His slider still appeared flat at
times and he couldn't put hitters away.
</P>
