<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Celebrates Birthday  </HEADLINE>
By REAGAN HAYNES
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- The historic home where Franklin D.
Roosevelt lived held a 65th birthday celebration Saturday for one
of the former president's best-known legacies: Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people, including Roosevelt's grandson, gathered to
for the event that included a re-enactment of the Roosevelt speech
that preceded the ''fireside chat'' and Social Security
bill-signing on Aug. 14, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's as Roosevelt said in his speech earlier, this is a
foundation for people, and it grows and changes with the times,''
Social Security Commissioner Kenneth Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   James Roosevelt discussed his grandfather's efforts on the
program that was part of the New Deal, a cornerstone of the FDR
administration. He also praised Eleanor Roosevelt's role in helping
launch the program that now covers 44 million American retirees,
disabled and dependents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her role as my grandfather's eyes and ears, her reports to him
of ... poverty and older America, inspired him to fight the good
fight,'' James Roosevelt said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven percent of American senior citizens live in poverty
despite the law, but the Social Security agency said the figure
would be 50 percent without the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an intergenerational system. I'm paying for my dad's
retirement and you're paying for your grandparents,'' Apfel said.
''It's changed with the times to last 65 years, and it will be
there 65 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt library: www.fdrlibrary.marist.edu/
</P>
<P>
   Social Security Agency: www.ssa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
