<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings' Moss Hurt in Exhibition  </HEADLINE>
By ARNIE STAPLETON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Randy Moss injured his left shoulder Saturday
night during the Minnesota Vikings' exhibition game against the New
Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays were negative, team trainer Chuck Barta said. However,
Moss needed MRIs on his left shoulder and on his ribs, which were
bruised.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't even want to guess,'' Barta said of the possibility
that the MRIs would show a dislocation or separation. He said he'd
have the results Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Barta said results of the X-rays were promising and led him to
be hopeful that the injury wasn't serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''The X-rays didn't show anything broken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dennis Green said he would be careful not to play Moss
until he's 100 percent again.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully, it's just a bruise,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Moss was injured after hurdling a defender and landing awkwardly
out of bounds following a 55-yard catch-and-run in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Moss earned Pro Bowl berths in each of his first two seasons in
the NFL. He was the offensive rookie of the year in 1998 after
catching 17 TD passes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his production slipped but he earned the Most
Outstanding Player award at the 2000 Pro Bowl after setting records
for catches (nine) and receiving yards (212), and scoring the final
touchdown in the NFC's 51-31 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Moss slipped to the Vikings with the 21st pick in the 1998 draft
after a brilliant but checkered college career that began at
Florida State and ended at Marshall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
